<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Diary of Nanjing Massacre to Appear in Autumn </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BERLIN, April 28 (Xinhua) -- The eight-volume diary of a
German, John Rabe, detailing Japanese atrocities in the massacre
in Nanjing in 1937, will be published in autumn this year.
</P>
<P>
A lengthy article, entitled "A Merchant Saves 250,000 People,"
was published by the Berlin-based Der Tagesspiegel on Sunday. It
said that Rabe, "a great friend of China," and as chief
representative of the German engineering giant Siemens at that
time, decided to stay in Nanjing to set up a security zone
together with some American friends, when the Japanese army
entered the city.
</P>
<P>
He housed some 250,000 impoverished Chinese who were unable to
flee from home, and helped them escape the Japanese massacre, the
article reported.
</P>
<P>
Rabe witnessed what the Japanese did when they entered Nanjing
and kept a detailed record of the Japanese atrocities against
unarmed Chinese.
</P>
<P>
In his 2,400-page diary, Rabe devoted more than 800 pages to
describing the horrors committed by Japanese soldiers during their
massacre of an estimated 300,000 Chinese people in the city in
1937.
</P>
<P>
"Any one who had callouses on his hands, blisters on his feet
or was short-haired, would be killed as a Chinese soldier by the
Japanese," Rabe wrote in his diary.
</P>
<P>
"Under such a pretext, the Japanese soldiers machine-gunned,
and blasted with grenades, thousands and thousands of Chinese to
death. For those who survived, the Japanese would pour gasoline
on them and burn them to death alive.
</P>
<P>
"Only one or two people survived eventually, and crawled to the
hospital and told others what had happened;
</P>
<P>
"The Japanese soldiers drove the Chinese to the riverside, or
to the banks of over 3,000 ponds, and committed the atrocity of
unparalleled savagery. The more than 3,000 ponds were all full of
corpses.
</P>
<P>
"The Japanese raped Chinese women, and those who were not
obedient were killed ruthlessly. Neither could girls aged seven
or eight nor old ladies over 70 years in age escape the brutality
once they fell in the hands of the Japanese;
</P>
<P>
"Many Chinese women were killed after being raped. We found
broken bits of beer bottles and bamboo spikes in the corpses of
some of the dead women."
</P>
<P>
In a report after he returned to Berlin in 1938, Rabe said that
they (he and his friends) "spent the days of December 1937
crawling to and fro on the corpses of the Chinese. We still
couldn't finish burying all the corpses till February 1 the next
year (1938)."
</P>
<P>
By the time Rabe returned to Berlin on February 22, 1938, more
than 30,000 Chinese corpses were still lying in the open, unburied
in Xiaguan, Nanjing.
</P>
<P>
The Der Tagesspiegel newspaper also published photos of the
massacre, and photos of Rabe and his family in Nanjing.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese version of Rabe's diary will be published by the
Nanjing People's Printing House in October this year, on the eve
of the 60 anniversary of the Nanjing Massacre.
</P>
<P>
Rabe's diaries and photographs were made public by his
grand-daughter, Ursula Reinhardt, in December last year, on the
59th anniversary of the siege of Nanjing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
