<HEADLINE> US New Home Sales Down by 2.5 Percent in March </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 28 (Xinhua) -- The sales of new homes in the
U.S. declined by 2.5 percent in March but remained strong as the
sales in February was the strongest in eleven years.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Commerce Department reported today that new homes sold at
a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 813,000 last month, down from
a rate of 834,000 in February which was the highest since April
1986.
</P>
<P>
The sales in the first three months of this year mark the first
time since 1978 that sales of new homes in the country have topped
the 800,000 level three times in a row.
</P>
<P>
The changes left the annual sales pace for the first quarter 8
percent higher than the fourth quarter. Strong sales reduced the
inventory of unsold homes at the end of March to 297,000, the
lowest in nearly three years.
</P>
<P>
The small decline in new home sales in March was led by a 16.1
percent drop in the Northeast. Sales also fell by 10.5 percent in
the South. But they rose 17.7 percent in the West and 2.5 percent
in the Midwest.
</P>
<P>
Thirty-year, fixed-rate mortgages averaged between 7.84 percent
and 7.97 percent in March and have topped 8 percent during April.
Analysts believe that the rising mortgage rates will eventually
curb home sales a bit later this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
