<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Personal Computer Market Speeds Up in First Quarter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, April 28 (Xinhua) -- Growth in the personal computer
market accelerated worldwide in the first quarter this year,
according to preliminary data released today by International Data
Corporation.
</P>
<P>
Unit shipments worldwide rose 16 percent over the first quarter
of 1996, compared to only 13 percent year-over-year growth in Q4
1996. The U.S. recorded a 20 percent increase, the fastest of any
major region, and the best quarterly domestic growth rate since
the end of 1995. But Dataquest, another major research group, said
the U.S. PC market grew 15 percent.
</P>
<P>
Analysts attributed the growth to the introduction of MMX
technology of Intel and a wide-range price cut of PCs.
</P>
<P>
Compaq once again led the market, both in the U.S. and
worldwide. Dell Computer edged out IBM to come in at third in the
U.S. market, Dell's highest position ever. It also claimed third
place in the worldwide rankings, behind Compaq and IBM.
</P>
<P>
The other major regions of the world were not quite as robust
as the United States. PC shipments in Western Europe rose 13
percent, better than in recent quarters, as corporate buying
picked up somewhat despite the weak economic conditions in major
countries. Economic uncertainty weighed upon sales in major Asian
markets as well, holding shipment growth in Japan to 14 percent
and in the rest of the Asia-Pacific region to 13 percent,
"unusually low for that fast-growing part of the world," the
company said.
</P>
<P>
Packard Bell NEC, number two in the U.S. and fourth worldwide,
showed signs of improvement from recent periods, which have been
plagued by manufacturing difficulties and falling sales. The
company's 799 U.S. dollar PC, introduced in January became Packard
Bell's best-selling model. The NEC brand of notebooks and premium
desktops also did well.
</P>
<P>
Making its maiden appearance in the worldwide top five is
Toshiba of Japan, which jumped 60 percent.  
</P>
</TEXT>
