<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 1600 GMT, April 28 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD -- Food supplies will be distributed throughout Iraq in
accordance with new rations as from next month, an Iraqi Trade
Ministry spokesman announced today.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi News Agency (INA) quoted the spokesman as saying
that the new rations were set in the light of the amounts of food
supplies imported in accordance with the memorandum of
understanding signed between Iraq with the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
The monthly food supply rations per capita will be as
follows: nine kilograms of wheat, 2.5 kilograms of rice, one
kilogram of vegetable oil, 350 grams of washing powder, 250 grams
of soap, one kilogram of legumes, the report said.
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW -- The explosion of a military depot in the far east
region of Russia halted dozens of trains on the Trans-Siberian
railway, the Interfax news agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
The explosion, which erupted Sunday afternoon, continued for
nearly a whole day and made rescue virtually impossible. Splinters
from exploding artillery shells were strewn around a radius of 12
kilometers.
</P>
<P>
The traffic on the Trans-Siberian railway, which passes near
the depot, was interrupted, with 25 passenger and 60 freight
trains halted.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- Jordan said today that it welcomes any efforts to hold
a summit, including Jordan, Egypt, the Palestinian National
Authority (PNA) and Israel, which is inteded to bring the peace
process back on track.
</P>
<P>
This came in remarks by Jordanian Minister of State for Media
Affairs, Samir Mutawe in an exclusive interview published by the
Jordanian newspaper "Al-Dustour" today.
</P>
<P>
Mutawe said that the Jordanian leadership welcomes any joint
Arab effort intended to bring the Middle East peace process back
on its proper track, but he said that the Egyptian proposal for
holding a four-nation summit has not yet been offered to Jordan's
political leadership. 
</P>
</TEXT>
