<HEADLINE> Spain's Largest Bank Opens Office in Shanghai </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, April 28 (Xinhua) -- Banco Santanter, Spain's largest
financial institution, today opened a representative office in
this, largest economic center of China.
</P>
<P>
The new office is the Spanish bank's second in China, with the
other in the Chinese capital of Beijing.
</P>
<P>
Emilio Botin, chairman of the bank group, said that the China
market is full of opportunities and potential, noting that his
bank will focus its Asian business in China.
</P>
<P>
The chairman revealed that his bank is talking with the
People's Bank of China, the central bank, for an early opening of
a China branch and wants to deal in business in the local currency.
</P>
<P>
The Spanish bank has invested more than 200 million US dollars
in infrastructure development in China.
</P>
<P>
The bank today also signed a letter of intent with a Shanghai
gas liquidation company, under which it will provide financial
consultance for the local firm's two projects, valued at 2.26
billion US dollars.
</P>
<P>
Official record shows that Shanghai currently has 154 overseas
financial institutions, including 47 branches and
sub-branches. Most of them have begun to reap profits.
</P>
<P>
China's financial opening-up has been accelerating in recent
years. Late last year and early this year the central bank
approved two batches of eight overseas banks to deal in the local
currency, the Renminbi yuan, on a trial basis in the Shanghai's
Pudong's New Area, an area separated from downtown Shanghai by the
Huangpu River.  
</P>
</TEXT>
