<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's Agriculture Minister Resigns </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, April 28 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's Agriculture Minister
Denis Norman announced his resignation here today from both the
government and active politics with effect from April 30.
</P>
<P>
He told reporters that his decision was not influenced by any
member of the government and did not indicate any disagreement
with government policies.
</P>
<P>
"After careful consideration, I feel the time has now arrived
for me to retire from active politics and in this regard, I
discussed the subject with his excellency, the president, at a
meeting held on April 9, 1997," he said.
</P>
<P>
"This afforded me the opportunity to thank the president for
the confidence he has shown in me during the years since
independence in 1980," Norman said.
</P>
<P>
Norman, 66, white, has served in the government for 15 years
since the southern African country declared independence 17 years
ago. He has been a minister for 12 years, mainly in the
Agriculture Ministry and once in the Transport Ministry.
</P>
<P>
There are rumors that he was losing popularity among white
commercial farmers especially after introducing an aggregate 10
percent levy for tobacco growers and merchants in 1996.
enditem

