<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Challenges for Pacific Rim Rugby Championship </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 28 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong return to the Pacific
Rugby Championship this year and hope to replac Canada as the
title holders.
</P>
<P>
But Hong Kong had first to overcome tournament underdogs Japan
in the opening match at Aberdeen Stadium here on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The two teams also played each other in the opening fixture of
the inaugural championship last year.
</P>
<P>
Despite outscoring Japan by four tries to three, Hong Kong went
down 34-27 in a thrilling encounter in Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong want to improve on their performance from last year
when the team won two out of their six outings on a home-and-away
basis against Canada, Japan and the United States.
</P>
<P>
All the four teams are expected to field their full strength
sides.
</P>
<P>
The curtain raiser to this Saturday's championship features the
Hong Kong Dragons against the Asian Barbarians made up of players
from China, Chinese Taipei, Sri Lanka, Singapore and Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
The Dragons will also play Chinese Taipei before the May 24
encounter between Hong Kong and defending champions Canada.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong Rugby Football Union (HKRFU) Secretary Peter Else
said, "This year's Pacific Rim Championship promises to be even
better than the inaugural tournament.
</P>
<P>
"All the teams are capable of beating one another. Everyone
realizes they are in with a chance and this will surely provide
some very exciting rugby," he said.
</P>
<P>
The championship will close on June 29, when hosts Japan plays
Hong Kong in the 10th and final match.  
</P>
</TEXT>
