<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Azerbaijani, Armenian Presidents Hold Talks in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, April 28 (Xinhua) -- Azerbaijani President Gaidar
Aliyev and Armenian President Levon Ter-Petrosyan this afternoon
held a 45-minute-long talk in Istanbul, Turkey, on the dispute of
the Norgorno-Karabakh.
</P>
<P>
The presidents of the two countries, both Turkey's neighbors,
failed to make any statement to the press.
</P>
<P>
The two presidents arrived in Istanbul today for a three-day
business conference of the Black Sea Economic Cooperation (BSEC).
</P>
<P>
As "mediator" of the dispute over the status of
Norgorno-Karabakh between Azerbaijan and Armenia, Turkish
President Suleyman Demirel said before their meeting that Turkey
would make efforts to mediate between the two countries in a bid
to establish peace in the Caucasus.
</P>
<P>
Demirel said: "It is easy to spoil peace, but it is difficult
to secure peace again."
</P>
<P>
The Turkish president was present at the meeting between Aliyev
and Petrosyan in the beginning, but left five minutes later.
</P>
<P>
Turkey is not only following the peace in the Caucasus, but
also the peace in the Middle East and Balkans, said Demirel.
</P>
<P>
On April 19, an armed conflict in the border area between
Azerbaijan and Armenia broke out again since the cease-fire was
secured between the two countries in 1994. More than 50
people were killed or wounded in the conflict which was the
largest one since 1994.
</P>
<P>
Azerbaijan and Armenia have made no progress in their talks
as there are differences over the status of the future of
Norgorno-Karabakh and the conditions for the deployment of
peace-keeping troops of the Organization of Security and
Cooperation in Europe (OSCE) in the region since the two
countries ceased conflicts in 1994. 
</P>
</TEXT>
