<HEADLINE> 5 Village Guards Killed in Southeastern Turkey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, April 28 (Xinhua) -- Five village guards were killed in
an armed clash with the illegal Kurdish Workers' Party (PKK)
rebels in southeastern Turkey linking neighboring Syria, the
semi-official Anatolia News Agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
The agency said that the clash broke out between the PKK
militants and the village guards early this morning as the
militants tried to attack Bagozu village in Dargecit town of
Mardin province.
</P>
<P>
The PKK guerrillas first opened fire at the village guards,
immediately killing five and wounding four others. In return, the
village guards shot dead two PKK rebels, said the report.
</P>
<P>
The agency also said that the wounded were rushed to Mardin
State Hospital for treatment.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, another group of PKK rebels today opened fire at
the center of Dargecit from mountainous area and the PKK group
escaped after the Turkish security forces responded, said the
report.
</P>
<P>
The agency added that large-scale operations were launched in
the region in a bid to capture the PKK rebels.
</P>
<P>
The PKK has been fighting a separatist war, which has claimed
over 21,000 lives in eastern and southeastern Turkey since August
1984. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
