<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Coffee Prices Expected to Be Higher in Zimbabwe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, April 28 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's average coffee price
for this marketing season is expected to be firmer and higher
than last year's 2,640 U.S. Dollars per ton following reduced
production in a number of coffee-producing countries.
</P>
<P>
Coffee Producers Association Chairman Philip Gifford said here
today some 30 percent of 12,000 tons of coffee in the southern
African country has already been committed in forward sales.
</P>
<P>
"The indications are that the market will be firmer and the
prices will be higher because of the problems in Kenya, the
unrest in Burundi and Rwanda, the social problems in Colombia and
the climate conditions in Brazil," Gifford said.
</P>
<P>
The difficulties facing these countries have lead to reduced
production, giving Zimbabwean producers an edge in the
international coffee market, he said.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe exports its coffee to European, America and Asia.
enditem

=04281744

=04281751
NNNN
01:52 01:52 g # PAB
</P>
