<HEADLINE> Israel Accused of Rounding Up Egyptians </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 28 (Xinhua) -- Egyptians accused Israel of
arresting Egyptian workers to pressure Egypt into releasing Azzam
Azzam, who is being held on charges of spying for the Israeli
Mossad, the Middle East Times reported in its latest edition.
</P>
<P>
The weekly quoted media reports as saying that Israel was
arresting large numbers of Egyptians on charges that they were
working in Israel without permits.
</P>
<P>
The economic daily Al Alam Al Youm said in a recent report that
Israel had begun a "wide-ranging campaign to detain Egyptians and
put them into the notorious Ayaluat prison, which is known for its
poor conditions."
</P>
<P>
The independent Egyptian daily further claimed that Israeli
Minister of Infrastructure and former general in the 1967 war
Ariel Sharon called for the detention.
</P>
<P>
On April 20, the opposition daily Al Ahrar supported the
charges, saying that Egyptians were detained on Sharon's orders.
</P>
<P>
"The campaign has been promoted by Sharon's call to the Israeli
Knesset to pressure Egypt to release Israelis held in Egypt on
charges of spying, forgery and drug trafficking," it said.
</P>
<P>
Rumors that Israel is seeking a deal with Egypt have abounded
since Israeli TV reported last December that Israel, which has
denied that Azzam has any links with Mossad, was ready to exchange
him for Egyptians held in its prisons.
</P>
<P>
According to the weekly Al Musawar newspaper, 20
spying-for-profit networks for Israel have been dismantled since
the signing of the Egyptian-Israeli peace treaty in March 1979.
</P>
<P>
There are altogether five Egyptians and Israelis who are
involved in two recent spy cases in Egypt. If convicted, they
might face the harshest penalty, life imprisonment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
