<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Chief Calls on Member States to Ratify CWC </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, April 28 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan on Monday called upon member states to ratify the
Chemical Weapons Convention (CWC)if they have not yet done so.
</P>
<P>
"The Secretary-General has just learned from the Mission of
Cuba to the United Nations that Cuba intends to submit its
instruments of ratification for the Chemical Weapons Convention on
Monday, 28 April," said a statement issued by the U.N. Spokesman's
Office.
</P>
<P>
"He welcomes this action and hopes that other nations that
other nations have not yet ratified will do so," the statement
said.
</P>
<P>
Ever since the Chemical Weapons Convention opened for signature
in Paris on January 1993, 164 countries have signed it. Eighty-one
countries have ratified the Convention and deposited their
instrument of ratification with the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
The United States, one of the two country which possesses large
quantity of chemical weapons, ratified the Convention last Friday.
The other country, which also possessed a large quantity of
chemical weapons but has not ratified it, is Russia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
