<BODY>
<HEADLINE> British Airways Urges Separation from Air Algeria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, April 28 (Xinhua) -- The British Airways today urged
French authorities to separate it from Air Algeria in the
Roissy-Charles de Gaulle airport of Paris, as they do in other
French airports.
</P>
<P>
The British Airways closed its reception counter today during
the time when Air Algeria, which has its reception counter next to
that of British Airways and share the same baggage conveyor belt
with it, was serving its passengers.
</P>
<P>
"This is not a problem concerning Air Algeria, but a problem
concerning the level of security established by each government
for a given company," said George Cooper, general director for
Europe of British Airways.
</P>
<P>
The British air company has also filed a suit against French
authorities for failing to provide enough security. A verdict
will be given by a Paris court on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Asked why Britain does not separate Air Algeria from other air
companies in London airports, Cooper said that the British
government assigns a different "level of security" to Air
Algeria than the French government, which regards the Algerian air
company as a high risk one.
</P>
<P>
Air Algeria, the only air company serving direct flight between
Algiers and Paris, resumed its flight between the two capitals
last Friday after a two-year suspension. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
