<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Major Urges Northern Irelanders Not to Vote for IRA </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 28 (Xinhua) -- In his last-ditch efforts to win
the upcoming election in May 1, Prime Minister John Major went to
Northern Ireland today for campaigning and called on local voters
to vote against Sinn Fein, the IRA's political wing.
</P>
<P>
"Anyone who votes Sinn Fein in this election is condoning the
violence," local media quoted Major as saying. "We have seen, I
hope, that people will cast their votes for the genuinely
democratic parties in Northern Ireland and I look forward to them
to doing that on Thursday this week."
</P>
<P>
He has lagged far behind the opposition Labor party in recent
opinion polls and seems to be toppled by Labor leader Tony Blair
on Thursday by a landslide victory.
</P>
<P>
IRA guerrillas, who have been fighting against the British rule
of Northern Ireland for nearly three decades, have caused chaos
and huge economic losses in British mainland in recent weeks with
bombs and bomb threats.
</P>
<P>
Major launched a peace plan together with the Irish government
in 1993, which was followed by IRA's ceasefire agreement in August
1994. But IRA broke it in February 1996 and resumed violent
actions.
</P>
<P>
Major has insisted that Sinn Fein will not be invited to the
multi-party peace talks until the IRA officially gives up
violence. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
