<DOCNO> XIE19970429.0049 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Former French PM Calls for More Liberal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, April 28 (Xinhua) -- Former French Prime Minister
Edouard Balladur said today that France should adopt a more
liberal socio-economic policy.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the daily Le Figaro due to be published on
Tuesday, Balladur said that a more liberal social and economic
policy means less public spending, less taxes, more contracts,
more social dialogue, more liberty and more flexibility.
</P>
<P>
"I am the supporter of an economy of liberty... It was when
resorting to more liberty that I succeeded in relaunching the
economic machine and began to reduce unemployment," he said in
reference to his mandate as prime minister in the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
Balladur, who is now parliamentary deputy of Paris for the
ruling Gaullist Rally for the Republic party, said that although
France now faces many problems, it is "on the good track."
</P>
<P>
He said that France now faces two long-term tasks: reduce its
public deficit to 2 percent of its gross domestic product and cut
taxes.
</P>
<P>
He suggested that the government "go further" in its plan to
cut 5,000 public jobs each year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
