<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-28 19:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey, Russia Reach Big Natural Gas Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, April 28 (Xinhua) -- Turkey and Russia today signed a
deal worth 13.5 billion U.S. dollars in Istanbul, the largest city
of Turkey, on supply of Russian natural gas in the next 25 years.
</P>
<P>
The accord was signed by Turkey's Energy Minister Recai Kutan
and Rem Vyakhirev, president of Gazprom, the giant Russian
natural gas producer and exporter. Kutan and Vyakhirev were in
Istanbul to attend a three-day business conference of the Black
Sea Economic Cooperation (BSEC).
</P>
<P>
At the signing ceremony, the two men told reporters that the
new natural gas deal would help guarantee Turkey's energy
security in the next century.
</P>
<P>
The natural gas will be sent to Turkey through an
existing pipeline running from Russia via Ukraine, Moldova,
Romania and Bulgaria, said Kutan.
</P>
<P>
He said that additional compressors, pumping stations and loop
pipes would be installed on the pipelines at a cost of 87 million
dollars, adding "Turkey's natural gas demand is increasing beyond
expectations."
</P>
<P>
Turkey's natural gas demand will increase more than threefold
to 27 billion cubic meters by the year of 2000 and more
than sevenfold to 60 billion cubic meters by 2010, local
economists said.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, Turkey consumed 6 billion cubic meters of natural gas
imported from Russia and 2 billion cubic meters of Liquefied
Natural Gas (LNG) from Algeria.
</P>
<P>
Turkey intends to buy LNG from Egypt and Nigeria and
plans to purchase 10 billion cubic meters of natural gas a
year from Iran through a new pipeline from Tabriz, Iran, to
Ankara, despite strong U.S. objections. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
