<HEADLINE> Uganda Enjoys 67 Percent Debt Reschedule from </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, April 28 (Xinhua) -- Uganda has enjoyed a 67
percent debt reschedule of the 68 million US Dollars owed
to the Italian government.
</P>
<P>
Reschedulling of the debt becomes effective this month.
</P>
<P>
The debt is to be paid in a period of 30 years at an interest
rate that will ensure that the net present value is reduced by 67
percent.
</P>
<P>
The debt reschedule agreement was signed here today by
Minister of State for Finance Basoga Nsadhu on behalf of Uganda and
visiting Italian Minister of State for Foreign Affairs in charge
of development cooperation Rino Serri.
</P>
<P>
The signing ceremony was witnessed by Permament Secretary in
the Ugandan Ministry of Finance Mutebile Emmanuel, Italian Ambassador
to Uganda Marcello Ricoveri and several senior officials from both
the Italian and Ugandan governments.
</P>
<P>
At the signing ceremony, Rino Serri reiterated that Italy
will do everyting possible to support Uganda's effort to develop in
areas like agriculture, health care, infrastructure and universal
primary education.
</P>
<P>
He also revealed that Uganda is ranked the seventh beneficiary
from the coffer of Italy in the world.
</P>
<P>
Nsadhu expressed Ugandan government's gratitude to the Italian
government for softening the debt burden Uganda owes it and referred
to it as an admirable gesture to a developing country like Uganda.
