<DOCNO> XIE19970429.0056 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bonn Plans Not to Use Euro in Public Services Until 2002 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, April 28 (Xinhua) -- German government today said that
public service sector in the country would not use the single
European currency, the Euro, until the year 2002 due to cost
reasons.
</P>
<P>
"Initial considerations... are for a uniform changeover of all
public administrative bodies from January 1, 2002," said the German
Finance Ministry in an interim report approved by the Bonn
government.
</P>
<P>
The European Union is due to introduce the Euro from January 1,
1999. At the first stage, however, the Euro would only be used for
accounting purposes during a three-year transition period from
1999 to 2002.
</P>
<P>
From January 1, 2002, the Euro banknotes and coins would be
issued and current national currencies, such as the German mark,
would cease to be legal tender at the latest from June 30, 2002.
</P>
<P>
German government said it could not introduce the Euro for
accounting purposes in public services, such as taxation, social
welfare payment and customs services, until 2002 due to the high
costs of managing two currency systems at the same time.
</P>
<P>
Unlike Germany, EU members such as Belgium, Ireland, Luxembourg
and the Netherlands are considering to introduce the Euro in
public administration from 1999. France, like Germany, plans to
wait until 2002.
</P>
<P>
Decision on which EU states will make the first wave to join
the Euro in 1999 will be made next April based on full economic
data from 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
