<HEADLINE> Food Shortage Pushes Up Inflation in Tanzania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, April 28 (Xinhua) -- Food shortage caused by
drought hitting Tanzania pushed up the rate of inflation to 17
percent in March from 13.8 percent in February.
</P>
<P>
Early this month, Tanzanian President Benjamin Mkapa announced
that about four million Tanzanians are facing food shortage and
need some 138,765 tons of cereals to sustain them for the next
five months.
</P>
<P>
He listed food deficit regions as Arusha, Coast, Dodoma,
Kilimanjaro, Lindi, Mara, Mwanza, Shinyanga, Singida, Tabora and
Tanga.
</P>
<P>
A senior official with the Bank of Tanzania (BoT) told the
official Daily News here today that bad roads in many parts of
the country affected transportation of food to those areas
suffering from food shortage.
</P>
<P>
The official said that in March road transport industry was
significantly affected by the government's directive for buses to
fix speed limiters amd many bus owners had failed to meet the
February 28 deadline.
</P>
<P>
The official, however, said that he believed that the problems
were temporary and the inflationary trends would soon be
reversed.
</P>
<P>
"We may even attain the 10 percent target by the end of next
June," he added.
</P>
<P>
He said that the government has continued to maintain a strict
fiscal policy and control spending. "All is well, things are not
out of control," he pointed out.  enditem

