<HEADLINE> ECOWAS Backs Efforts to Find Hidden Arms in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, April 28 (Xinhua) -- The Authorities of the Economic
Community of West African States (ECOWAS) today expressed fully
support for the current military operations to recover hidden
arms in Liberia.
</P>
<P>
An ECOWAS assessment team in Liberia commended particularly
the ECOWAS peacekeeping force, known as ECOMOG, for the recent
recovery of a large cache of artillery weapons from Nimba county
near the border between Liberia and Cote d'Voire.
</P>
<P>
The team, led by Nigeria's Foreign Affairs Minister Tom Ikimi,
is in Liberia to assess the country's preparation for the
forthcoming elections slated for May 30.
</P>
<P>
During a visit to the ECOMOG headquarters in Monrovia, capital
of Liberia, Ikimi said despite the success of the disarmament
exercise, ECOWAS was not oblivious of the fact that there were
still arms hidden in the country.
</P>
<P>
ECOWAS was impressed by and would continue to support the
efforts to recover them, he added, quoted by the News Agency of
Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
Ikimi was accompanied by the foreign ministers of Guinea and
Ghana, the special envoy of the U.S. president to Liberia, the
chief military observer of the U.N. Observer Mission in Liberia
and the U.S. ambassador to Liberia.
</P>
<P>
According to ECOMOG Commander Maj.-Gen. Victor Malu, the arms
discovered in Nimba last week include some of the most deadly and
expensive artillery weapons in the world.
</P>
<P>
ECOWAS, a sub-regional organization of the 16 west African
countries for common development, has been making efforts to
bring lasting peace in Liberia. Nigeria now holds the
chairmanship of it. 
</P>
</TEXT>
