<HEADLINE> First Consignment of Goods for Burundi to Leave </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, April 28 (Xinhua) -- The first consignment of
goods destined for Burundi, since the easing of trade sanctions
by the leaders of the Great Lakes region this month, is expected
to leave Kigoma port, western Tanzania, on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Kigoma Regional Commissioner Yusuf Makamba told the official
Daily News from the town of Kigoma today over the telephone that
a total of 460 tons of fertilizer would leave tomorrow aboard two
vessels.
</P>
<P>
"There are 2,043 tons of fertilizer piled up in Kigoma, 220
tons have been loaded on MV Muliro and 240 tons on MV Buyonama.
Both vessels are registered in Burundi and would leave tomorrow
or the day after tomorrow," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said that the fertilizer was ordered by Mossrs Appro of
Burundi on behalf of the Burundi Ministry of Agriculture.
</P>
<P>
The vessels, which sailed from Burundi to pick the cargo, would
come back to continue ferrying the remaining lot, he added.
</P>
<P>
He said that the goods qualified to be released in the light
of the eased sanctions, still laying at Kigoma, further included
444 tons of building materials, 15 tons of wheat flour and 10
tons of salt.
</P>
<P>
The leaders of the Great Lakes region, who met in Arusha,
northern Tanzania this month, lifted santions on food,
agricultural produce, educational materials, medicines and
construction materials.  enditem


