<HEADLINE> Qian Qichen: Prospect for Sino-US Relations Promising </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 28 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Vice Premier and
Foreign Minister Qian Qichen said today that the prospect of
relations between China and the United States is "promising"
although there exist differences over some issues between the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a joint news conference at the start of talks with
U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, Qian Qichen said,
"China and the United States share the aspiration to resolve the
questions as soon as possible.... I believe that as time goes by,
these questions will be resolved."
</P>
<P>
The vice premier, who arrived in Washington this morning, said
there has been a new momentum since the latter half of last year,
and he came to Washington for the preparation of the mutual state
visits of Chinese President Jiang Zemin and U.S. President Bill
Clinton to keep the momentum to a new stage.
</P>
<P>
"President Jiang Zemin's visit to the United States this fall
will be the major topic in our discussions," he said.
</P>
<P>
Albright said the Clinton administration will uphold the Most
Favored Nation trade status for China, saying: "We believe it is
very important for the MFN to go forward.... It is a strategic
imperative for this relationship to go forward and the trade
relationship is very important in that regard."
</P>
<P>
Asked about China's entry into the World Trade Organization,
Qian Qichen told reporters that "questions that are remaining
would be resolved" as talks on the issue are "positive ones."
</P>
<P>
With regard to the allegations that China has funneled money to
influence U.S. politics, Qian Qichen categorically dismissed them
as nonsensical.
</P>
<P>
"It is very usual for people to seek political contribution and
money politics in the United States. But that has nothing to do
with China," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
