<HEADLINE> US Asks Europeans to Curb Trade With Iran </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 28 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright is asking European nations to extend their
brief suspension of trade with Iran.
</P>
<P>
The request was made by Albright in a message over the weekend
to the European Union foreign ministers, who are due to meet
Tuesday in Luxembourg and will reportedly resume their "critical
dialogue" with Iran.
</P>
<P>
Undersecretary of State Peter Tarnoff was sent to Europe last
week to ask the Europeans to join the U.S. trade embargo against
Iran.
</P>
<P>
State Department spokesman Nicholas Burns told a news briefing
today that the U.S. hopes to cooperate with the Europeans in
dealing the relations with Iran.
</P>
<P>
On April 10, a German court ruled that Iranian leaders ordered
the September 17, 1992 killings of four Iranian dissidents at a
Berlin restaurant. Iran denied the charge.
</P>
<P>
The EU nations withdrew their envoys from Tehran and suspended
their policy of trading with Iran on April 10 after the ruling
of the German court.
</P>
<P>
The EU is expected to decide to end the suspension of trading
with Iran. The U.S. hopes the EU will follow and join the embargo
permanently against Iran but the EU opposes the measure, seeking a
policy of "critical dialogue."
</P>
<P>
Burns said, "We are realistic. We don't think the European
Union is going to adopt our policy." 
</P>
</TEXT>
