<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Factory Orders for Durable Goods Down 3 percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 29 (Xinhua) -- Orders to U.S. factories for
durable goods plunged by 3 percent in March, the biggest drop in
seven months, the U.S. Commerce Department reported today.
</P>
<P>
The department said that orders for durable goods, items
expected to last for more than three years, totaled a seasonally
adjusted 171.5 billion dollars in March, down from 176.8 billion
in February.
</P>
<P>
It was the largest decline since orders fell by 3.6 percent in
last August and also the first drop since December.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the U.S. government also revised the increase of
orders in February down to 0.8 percent, weaker than initially
estimated 1.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
The report showed that demands shrank in all major categories
in March. Orders for transportation equipment dropped 4.3 percent
after falling 7.3 percent in February. Orders for both aircraft
and motor vehicles had decreased.
</P>
<P>
Excluding transportation sector, orders were also down by 2.6
percent, the steepest decline since a 3 percent decrease in June
1991.
</P>
<P>
Bookings for electronic and other electrical equipment fell 5.9
percent, resulting mostly from fewer orders for electronic
components and communications equipment. This category had posted
jumps of 7.7 percent in February and 17.8 percent in January.
</P>
<P>
Orders for industrial machinery and equipment were down by 1.2
percent and for primary metals, off 0.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
The backlog of unfilled orders, which had suggested growing
demand recently, fell by 3.5 percent, the first decline since last
August. Shipments rose 0.7 percent, the third straight advance.
</P>
<P>
The orders for durable goods are considered a key gauge of U.S.
manufacturing strength. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970429.0074 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South Korea's Current Account Deficit Rises Sharply </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, April 29 (Xinhua) -- South Korea's current account
deficit rose sharply in the first quarter of the year, hitting
7.94 billion U.S. dollars, a report of the Bank of Korea said
today.
</P>
<P>
The figure, which was 71.1 percent higher than the same period
last year, accounted for half of the amount of 14 to 16 billion
dollars that the government budgeted for the whole year.
</P>
<P>
However, the current account situation is likely to improve
because the nation's exports are expected to rebound rapidly from
a long setback, now there has been a recovery of the prices of its
main export items, government officials said.
</P>
<P>
As a result of the price recovery, the current account deficit
in March, which was 2.27 billion dollars, was significantly
reduced from January's 3.16 billion dollars and February's 2.5
billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
The trade deficit also showed a downward trend in the first
quarter.
</P>
<P>
It dropped to 1.4 billion dollars in March from the 1.83
billion dollars in February and 2.34 billion dollars in January.
</P>
<P>
The current account balance measures the flow of goods and
services, and investment income and other monetary transfers of a
country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
