<HEADLINE> Central China Train Crash Kills 90 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, April 29 (Xinhua) -- Two passenger trains crashed
today in central-south China's Hunan Province, killing 90 people
and leaving more than 300 injured.
</P>
<P>
The crash occurred at 10:48 a.m., at the Rongjiawan Station on
the Beijing-Guangzhou Railway, one of China's railway transport
arteries. The station is in Yueyang County in northern Hunan.
</P>
<P>
Witnesses said that the No. 324 train, which was travelling
north from Kunming, capital of southwest China's Yunnan Province,
to Zhengzhou, capital of central China's Henan Province, collided
with the rear of the No. 818 train, which was stationary on the
line at the time, having been on its way from Changsha to Linxiang
City.
</P>
<P>
Thirteen carriages of the two trains were derailed,
witnesses said.
</P>
<P>
Senior Party and government officials of Hunan Province, a
deputy railways minister and more than 1,100 policemen and medical
workers immediately rushed to the crash site to carry out rescue
work. More than 90 of the seriously-injured passengers are now
receiving emergency treatment.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, it is learned that the accident, the cause of which
is still under investigation, did not affect the smooth operation
of the Beijing-Guangzhou Railway. 
</P>
</TEXT>
