<HEADLINE> Chinese Troops in Hong Kong to Wear New Uniforms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 29 (Xinhua) -- The troops of the People's
Liberation Army (PLA) to be stationed in Hong Kong will start
wearing a new generation of uniforms as of May 1, the PLA's
General Logistics Department said today.
</P>
<P>
The troops to be stationed in Hong Kong will march into Hong
Kong on July 1 in the new military uniforms, the department said.
</P>
<P>
The current uniforms of the PLA, known as Style-87, were first
used in 1988 but are now regarded as unsuitable, it said.
</P>
<P>
China began designing a new generation of uniforms for use into
the 21st century in early 1993, and the new uniforms to be used by
the troops in Hong Kong were made on the basis of that generation.
</P>
<P>
Compared with the current uniforms, the new ones are
significantly improved in structure, material, color, adornments
and match-up, according to the department.
</P>
<P>
The main hue of the new uniforms will be brown-green for the
army, white and dark blue for the navy, and sky blue for the air
force.
</P>
<P>
The new uniforms, which have more varieties for different
purposes, carry the Chinese characters for "August 1" and "The
Chinese People's Liberation Army" as well as designs of five
stars, Tiananmen Square, wheatsheaves and the Great Wall. They
also carry designs of olive branches and the insignia of
the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region, the department said.
</P>
<P>
China will start use the new uniforms for the entire armed
forces around the year 2000 if conditions are ripe by then, the
department said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
