<HEADLINE> EU Ambassadors to Return to Iran Soon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUXEMBOURG, April 29 (Xinhua) -- European Union (EU) countries
will send their ambassadors back to Iran soon in a move seen as
indicating they are not prepared to damage lucrative ties with the
country.
</P>
<P>
A meeting of EU foreign ministers today also decided to keep
its "critical dialogue" with Iran under suspension, and freeze
official bilateral ministerial visits.
</P>
<P>
An EU diplomat in Tehran was quoted as saying earlier that the
first wave of ambassadors could return before the end of this week.
</P>
<P>
The 15-nation EU urged Iran to respect international law and
refrain from "terrorist acts." It urged Iran to abide by its
commitments to non-proliferation of mass destruction weapons and
the protection of human rights.
</P>
<P>
It also asked Iran to ratify the Chemical Weapons Convention,
which bans the use and production of chemical weapons.
</P>
<P>
Relations between the EU and Iran were strained when all EU
countries, except Greece, recalled their ambassadors to Iran
earlier this month after a German court, on April 10, ruled that
Tehran's leadership organized the murder of four Kurdish
dissidents in Berlin in 1992.
</P>
<P>
Iran, denying any involvement in the murders, expelled four
German diplomats and has since taken a tough stance toward EU
criticism. 
</P>
</TEXT>
