<HEADLINE> Bomb Threats Forces Closure of London Motorways </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 29 (Xinhua) -- Just 48 hours before the British
elections on May 1, bomb threats forced the closure of large
stretches of four major motorways into London, blocking the way of
thousands of commuters.
</P>
<P>
Police said they received coded telephone threats at 6:50
a.m. today, the typical IRA warning, and had to close parts of the
M-1 motorway leading into London from northern England, and the
M-25 ring road around the capital which links to the Channel ports
as well as Heathrow and Gatwick airports.
</P>
<P>
Parts of the M-20 and the M-26 were also shut, bringing the
total affected motorway to more than 50 miles (80 km).
</P>
<P>
Heathrow airport's terminal for European flights had to be
closed for 22 minutes after a coded phone alert. Two terminals at
Gatwick, the other London airport, were also evacuated after
threatening calls.
</P>
<P>
Facing strong opposition from the Irish Republican Army against
British rule in Northern Ireland, Prime Minister John Major vowed
the government would not be moved by the terrorist acts.
</P>
<P>
"I don't think the British people are going to be moved by
this. They have made their judgement of the IRA. You can't cower
the British people like this," he told BBC radio.
</P>
<P>
The IRA, fighting against British rule of Northern Ireland for
more than two decades, has staged a string of bomb attacks and
hoaxes on roads, railways and airports during the election
campaign.
</P>
<P>
Sinn Fein, the political wing of IRA, is bidding to land three
seats in the British parliament in Thursday's election.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, while touring Northern Ireland for the campaign,
Major urged local voters not to vote for Sinn Fein. Voting for
Sinn Fein was a vote for violence, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
