<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France Hails Enforcement of Chemical Weapons Convention </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, April 29 (Xinhua) -- France today hailed the enforcement
of the Chemical Weapons Convention designed to ban the
development, production, stockpiling and use of chemical weapons
in the world.
</P>
<P>
"This convention is the first treaty of disarmament of
universal vocation, outlawing an entire category of weapons of
mass destruction, and effectively verifiable by a device of
multilateral control," said French Foreign Ministry spokesman
Jacques Rummelhardt.
</P>
<P>
He said the text was "a new positive signal given to the cause
of disarmament and (nuclear) non-proliferation." It followed the
indefinite extension in May 1995 of the Nuclear Non-Proliferation
Treaty, and the approval of the Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty in
the United Nations General Assembly in September 1996.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said France would continue to uphold the ban on
production of fissile materials for nuclear arms, of biological
weapons, and of anti-personnel land mines.
</P>
<P>
France also called on all countries to sign the convention,
which calls for the destruction of all chemical weapons of mass
destruction in the next decade.
</P>
<P>
The convention was finalized in Paris in January 1993 after 10
years of negotiations, and formally entered into force today.
</P>
<P>
Up to now, 165 states have signed the treaty and 87 countries
ratified it in time for the April 29 deadline.
</P>
<P>
Among the five permanent Security Council members, Britain,
China, France and the United States have ratified the treaty,
leaving Russia the only one yet to do so.
</P>
<P>
China ratified the convention last December and submitted the
instruments of ratification to the United Nations Friday to become
one of the signatory states to the convention. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
