<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Veteran Wang Leads China to 3-1 Victory over S. Korea </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANCHESTER, England, April 29 (Xinhua) -- Chinese table tennis
veteran Wang Tao, who delayed his retirement to check tenacious
South Koreans in the world championships, proved his value by
snatching two clutch points from the longtime rivals at the team
semi-finals here on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The 29-year-old Wang, who has excellent record against South
Koreans, wrapped up China's 3-1 victory by nipping Kim Taek Soo
21-12, 16-21, 21-17.
</P>
<P>
It was a sweet revenge for China, which has lost to South Korea
three times since the 1995 Worlds where it edged out South Korea
3-2 en route to winning the championship.
</P>
<P>
Double Olympic champion Liu Guoliang won the opening game for
China as he beat Kim 21-14, 22-20 in a clash of the world best
penholders.
</P>
<P>
The first set loss jolted Kim out of lethargy as he held Liu to
19-19 in the second set with strong topspin forehands. But a
wayward backhand return and a strong smash by Liu denied him a
chance to even the score.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese fast-attacker held a poor record against Kim, who
beat Liu twice last year, in a world all-star event and the Asian
championships.
</P>
<P>
Wang, competing in his fourth championships, grabbed the second
game as he nipped 72nd-ranked Ou Sang Eun 21-12, 21-7.
</P>
<P>
The 20-year-old Ou, who has beaten Wang once early this year,
looked nervous throughout the game and failed to release his
powerful forehands.
</P>
<P>
South Korean veteran Yoo Nam Kyu, ranked 19th in the world,
pulled one point back at the third game as he outplayed world top
player and defending singles champion Kong Linghui 21-18, 10-21,
21-18.
</P>
<P>
"We had a really tough match," said Chinese head coach Cai
Zhenhua. "South Koreans always play above their level in big event
but Wang Tao and Liu Guoliang played even better today."
</P>
<P>
China, which eliminated world runner-up Sweden in the quarter-
finals on Monday, will take on the winner of Germany and France
semi-final.
</P>
<P>
Cai, who declined to predict the final result, said instead
that China has more good players than Germany and France.
</P>
<P>
"We have cleared the biggest threats on China's road to its
12th world team championship -- Sweden and South Korea," the
Chinese coach said.
</P>
<P>
Cai warned his players not to relax their vigilance in the
final. "Germany has top European player Jorg Rosskopf and France
has 1993 world champion Jean-Philippe Gatien, you should be on a
high alert," he told his proteges who were celebrating their
victory over South Korea. 
</P>
</TEXT>
