government could not fix some of the country's biggest domestic
problems and said private citizens must fill the gap. The
president promised to push more Federal workers to volunteer as
private citizens, and announced 27 million dollars in Government
initiatives to encourage volunteerism.
</P>
<P>
The Wall Street Journal:
</P>
<P>
-- Secretary of Defense Cohen said a Pentagon review now under
way will emphasize weapons modernization. The report is due to be
presented to Clinton soon, and the administration, in budget
proposals, has shown willingness to cut troop strength further.
The review may spare from cancellation three types of jet fighters
being developed.
</P>
<P>
-- The Justice Department began an investigation of alleged
mismanagement and misconduct by the INS citizenship program, which
naturalized more than one million people in 1995 and 1996. Some
180,000 were processed before FBI checks were done. Republicans
charge the program was rushed to beef up voter rolls in the 1996
election.
</P>
<P>
USA Today:
</P>
<P>
-- Police obtained arrest warrants Monday for six members of an
armed separatist group holed up in the remote Davis Mountains
after the group released two hostages in exchange for a jailed
comrade. 
