<HEADLINE> France Denounces Kabila Ultimatum on Refugees </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, April 29 (Xinhua) -- The French government today
denounced the ultimatum of Zairian rebel leader Laurent-Desire
Kabila demanding that the United Nations High Commission for
Refugees (UNHCR) repatriate tens of thousands of Rwandan Hutu
refugees within 60 days.
</P>
<P>
"We share the view expressed by our American partners and by
the Secretary General of the United Nations (Kofi Annan), who
refused to have a limit imposed on the UNHCR to carry out the
operations of repatriation," Foreign Ministry spokesman Jacques
Rummelhardt said.
</P>
<P>
He said France would finance a U.N. inquiry into the reported
massacre of Hutu refugees by the Zairian rebels. This was
expected to be launched within weeks and would produce a report to
go to the United Nations General Assembly by June 30.
</P>
<P>
Kabila said on Sunday that the UNHCR should repatriate 30,000
to 60,000 Hutu refugees from the rebel-controlled area in eastern
Zaire. 
</P>
