<DOCNO> XIE19970429.0110 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Debt Payments Grow in EU Governments' Spending </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, April 29 (Xinhua) -- Government debt payments by
European Union (EU) member countries have made up a growing share
in their spending in the past decade, Eurostat, the EU's
statistical office, said in a report today.
</P>
<P>
Interest payments' share in the governments' current and
capital spending rose from seven percent in 1986 to a record 11
percent in 1995. This "limited the room for maneuver in
government expenditure," the report said after analyzing figures
from 10 of the EU's 15 members.
</P>
<P>
Belgium and Italy spend a fifth of their public expenditure on
debt payments, while a number of other members spend a tenth.
</P>
<P>
Italy recorded the largest increase in 1995, going from 21.5
percent of its spending in 1994 to 23.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
The debt payments' average portion in the governments' Gross
Domestic Product (GDP) grew from three percent in 1980 to 5.4
percent in 1995.
</P>
<P>
Total interest payments by the EU's 15 members in 1996 stood at
362 billion ECUs (413 billion U.S. dollars), for which Germany and
Italy accounted for 47 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970429.0111 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manila Stocks Suffer Biggest Plunge in 2 Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 29 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine Stock Exchange
index fell by 128.87 points today to close at 2,708.44 points,
suffering the sharpest plunge in more than two years.
</P>
<P>
The 4.5 percentage decline was the biggest drop since the
bourse fell 5.7 percent on January 13, 1995 after the Mexican
currency crisis in late 1994.
</P>
<P>
It was also the lowest close since January 11, 1996 when the
index ended at 2664.73 points.
</P>
<P>
Turnover totaled 7.356 billion shares today, with a value of
3.632 billion pesos (about 139.69 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
It has been the ninth time that the Stock Exchange index, a
basket of 30 companies, crashed in the month. On April 3-9, it
slumped by a total of 200 points in seven consecutive days.
</P>
<P>
On April 22, it fell again by 84.53 points, or 2.9 percent to
close at 2,860.45 points, the biggest drop in five months.
</P>
<P>
According to analysts, today's plunge was due to the withdrawal
of foreign funds amid the panic selling in the market and fears
that the Philippine peso will further depreciate against U.S.
dollars.
</P>
<P>
The selling was caused by speculations that the property sector
in the country will collapse like that in Thailand, analysts said,
adding the stock prices of property developers and banks suffered
heavy losses. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
