<DOCNO> XIE19970429.0112 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vice-Premier on Soil, Water Conservation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 29 (Xinhua) -- Vice-Premier Jiang Chunyun called
for more funds to support the country's fight against expanding
soil erosion, when attending the Sixth National Conference on Soil
and Water Conservation here today.
</P>
<P>
China should make concrete efforts to stop soil erosion,
otherwise there will be no sustainable economic and social
development for the Chinese people, he said.
</P>
<P>
He explained that it is a long-term task for China to fight
against soil erosion, although some achievements have been made in
this field.
</P>
<P>
According to sources at the conference, the total of eroded
land that China has tackled in a comprehensive way has reached
about 700,000 sq km over the past four decades, and the country's
total investment in this area reached seven billion yuan in the
past five years.
</P>
<P>
But China's overall situation of soil and water conservation
nationwide has continued to worsen, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
Chinese legislators have worked out laws on water and soil
conservation in order to improve the Chinese people's awareness of
the importance of environmental protection.
</P>
<P>
Jiang said that governments at all levels should help farmers
in the poverty-stricken areas to get rid of poverty, and keep a
close eye on environmental protection at the same time.
</P>
<P>
"More work should be done to bring soil erosion in the
country's seven major river valleys under control, and Chinese
cities should also take precautions against increasing soil
erosion," he warned.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the Chinese vice-premier urged governments at all
levels to take more measures to tighten up their supervision of
soil and water conservation, and implement the country's laws on
soil and water conservation in a serious way. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
