<HEADLINE> Official: Iran Not Militarily Dependent on Europe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, April 29 (Xinhua) -- Iranian foreign policy authorities
said today that the European Union's potential ban on arm
sales to Iran will not affect Tehran a bit because Iran is
not dependent on European countries for the procurement of its
arms.
</P>
<P>
Mahmoud Vaezi, Deputy Foreign Minister for Euro-American Affairs,
made the statement while he attended the opening ceremony of
the ECO ministerial meeting which opened here today.
</P>
<P>
As to the reports that EU member states will also decide to
stop issuance of visas to officials below the ministerial level in
their special meeting in Luxembourg today, the Iranian deputy
foreign minister commented that the decision would cause trouble
to the EU member states rather than Iran.
</P>
<P>
"This is no way to punish Iran since the consequences would be
debilitating for both sides and may be more troublesome to Europe
than Iran," he added.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian Parliament today issued a eight-point statement,
urging the Iranian government to stop dialog with EU countries
and the EU to arrest and hand over Iran's anti-government
activists in Europe.
</P>
<P>
As to the EU's ministerial meeting in Luxembourg today,
Iranian Foreign Minister Ali Akbar Velayati said on Sunday that
Iran has no expectation from European Union countries and they
can do whatever they like.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that Iran wants to have good relations with
European countries "but what is more important for us is the
observance of our principles in the foreign policy."
</P>
<P>
The relations between Iran and EU countries took a turn of
worse when Berlin court accused the Iranian leadership of ordering
the murder of four Kurdish leaders in Germany in 1992. All EU
members, except Greece, recalled their ambassadors in Tehran in
protest against the involvement of Iranian leaders in the case. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
