<HEADLINE> Rebels Responsible for Massacre: Philippine Military </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 29 (Xinhua) -- Investigators have found that
Muslim rebels were responsible for the killing of 10 students and
a teacher in the southern Philippines last month, a senior
military official said today.
</P>
<P>
The source, who requested anonymity, said the investigators
found the artillery causing the massacre was most likely fired
from a main camp of the Moro Islamic Liberation Front (MILF), a
major rebel group in the southern Mindanao.
</P>
<P>
The military and the rebels blamed each other for being
responsible for the killing in Buldon, Maguindanao province, where
they have had sporadic clashes since the beginning of the year.
</P>
<P>
The investigators informed the military of their findings
before releasing it to the public, according to the official.
</P>
<P>
He said investigators visited the explosion site and found that
the tragedy was caused not by a 105mm howitzer as reported
earlier, but by a smaller type which could be an 81mm or 60mm.
</P>
<P>
However, investigators learned that the military was stationed
9 to 10 kilometers away from the site and that the maximum range
of an 81mm or 61mm mortar was only 3.5 kilometers.
</P>
<P>
The investigators believed that the MILF rebels may have
mishandled their own mortars which killed the 11 civilians, the
official said.
</P>
<P>
The massacre has produced a negative impact on the country's
peace process. In their third round of low-level talks last week,
the two sides did not make any substantial progress except
agreeing to observe a local truce they have already signed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
