<HEADLINE> Missing Surveyors in Indonesia's Irian Jaya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, April 29 (Xinhua) -- Four employers of a road
surveying company who escaped an armed attack by the Free Papua
Movement (OPM) were found safe by a local military task force,
reports reaching here today from Irian Jaya said.
</P>
<P>
Armed OPM members opened fire at a team of six surveyors and 10
porters in Akiba village in the central mountainous region of
Irian Jaya Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Two surveyors were killed on the spot.
</P>
<P>
Earlier reports said eight workers went missing after they fled
into the forest during the attack.
</P>
<P>
Another report said the district military command and police
have launched a manhunt for the OPM members.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the OPM took at least 42 people as hostages,
including Indonesian scientists and workers as well as seven
Europeans.
</P>
<P>
Four Indonesian hostages were killed during a rescue operation.
</P>
<P>
The OPM, known as a security disturbance group, has been
fighting for a separate state in the area since the early 1960s,
before Irian Jaya was integrated into Indonesia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
