<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South Korea Pulls One Point Back in Men's Semis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANCHESTER, England, April 29 (Xinhua) -- South Korean veteran
Yoo Nam Kyu pulled one point back as China led 2-1 in the men's
team semi-finals of the World Table Tennis Championships here on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The 29-year-old Yoo outplayed world top player and defending
singles champion Kong Linghui 21-18, 10-21, 21-18 in the third
game.
</P>
<P>
Chinese veteran Wang Tao, who delayed his retirement for a
possible meeting with South Koreans in the world championships,
nipped Ou Sang Eun in straight sets in the second game.
</P>
<P>
The 29-year-old Wang, who holds excellent record against South
Koreans, beat the 72nd-ranked Ou 21-12, 21-7 to put China 2-0
ahead.
</P>
<P>
The 20-year-old Ou, who has beaten Wang once early this year,
looked nervous throughout the game and failed to release his
powerful forehands.
</P>
<P>
Double Olympic champion Liu Guoliang had put China one up as he
beat Kim Taek Soo in the opening game.
</P>
<P>
World No. 3 Liu downed Kim 21-14, 22-20 in a clash of the world
top penholders.
</P>
<P>
The first set loss jolted Kim out of lethargy and he held Liu
to 19-19 in the second set, but a wayward backhand return and a
strong smash by Liu denied him a chance to even the score.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese fast-attacker held a poor record against Kim, who beat
Liu twice last year, in a world all-star event and the Asian
championships.
</P>
<P>
South Korea has beaten China three times since the last world
championships where it finished third, trailing China and Sweden.
</P>
</TEXT>
