<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Beats S. Korea 3-1 in Men's Team Semis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANCHESTER, England, April 29 (Xinhua) -- Chinese table tennis
veteran Wang Tao, who delayed his retirement to check South
Koreans in the world championships, proved his value by snatching
two points from the longtime rivals at the men's team semi-finals
here on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The 29-year-old Wang, who has excellent record against South
Koreans, wrapped up China's 3-1 victory by nipping Kim Taek Soo
21-12, 16-21, 21-17.
</P>
<P>
It was a sweet revenge for China, who has lost to South Korea
three times since the 1995 Worlds where it edged out South Korea
3-2 en route to winning the championship.
</P>
<P>
Double Olympic champion Liu Guoliang had put China one up as he
beat Kim in the opening game.
</P>
<P>
World No. 3 Liu downed No. 5 Kim 21-14, 22-20 in a clash of the
world top penholders.
</P>
<P>
The first set loss jolted Kim out of lethargy and he held Liu
to 19-19 in the second set with strong topspin forehands, but a
wayward backhand return and a strong smash by Liu denied him a
chance to even the score.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese fast-attacker held a poor record against Kim, who
beat Liu twice last year, in a world all-star event and the Asian
championships.
</P>
<P>
Wang, competing in his fourth championships, grabbed the second
game as he nipped 72nd-ranked Ou Sang Eun 21-12, 21-7.
</P>
<P>
The 20-year-old Ou, who has beaten Wang once early this year,
looked nervous throughout the game and failed to release his
powerful forehips.
</P>
<P>
South Korean veteran Yoo Nam Kyu, ranked 19th in the world,
pulled one point back from the third game as he outplayed world
top player and defending singles champion Kong Linghui 21-18,
10-21, 21-18. 
</P>
</TEXT>
