<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S'pore Gov't Commits $2 Billion on IT in Education </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, April 29 (Xinhua) -- The Singapore government will
commit two billion Singapore dollars (about 1.4 billion U.S.
dollars) from 1997 to 2002 to implement a national plan to use
information technology (IT) in education.
</P>
<P>
The Singapore's Masterplan for IT in Education, unveiled by
Minister for Education Teo Chee Hean here Monday, but embargoed
until today, lays out a comprehensive strategy for creating an
IT-based teaching and learning environment in every school.
</P>
<P>
"It will be one of our key strategies for equipping our young
with the skills that are critical for the future -- creative
thinking, the ability to learn independently and continuously, and
effective communication," the minister said at the launch of the
Masterplan for IT in Education.
</P>
<P>
The goals of the plan are to enhance linkages between the
school and the world around it, so as to expand and enrich the
learning environment; to encourage creative thinking and life-long
learning; to encourage innovative processes in education and, to
promote administrative and management excellence in the education
system, Teo said.
</P>
<P>
He said that the government will commit two billion Singapore
dollars from this year to 2002 to implement this plan, which
includes funds for computers, full networking of the schools,
physical renovations, software and courseware, and teacher
training.
</P>
<P>
Subsequently, another 600 million Singapore dollars, or about
416.67 million U.S. dollars at current exchange rate, a year will
be provided to maintain and replace hardware, develop new
software, and for the continuous training of teachers, he said.
</P>
<P>
The target of the plan to be achieved by the year 2002 is for
students to have hands-on use of computers for 30 percent of their
curriculum time, the education minister said, adding that this
would mean providing one computer for every two students.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970429.0133 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-29 11:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt Calls for Concerted Arab Water Strategy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 29 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak
today urged Arab countries to coordinate their efforts in
preserving and developing water resources.
</P>
<P>
"As the Arab demand for limited water is ever increasing, it
is incumbent to find an orchestrated Arab plan to help develop
water resources," the president said in a message addressed to
the ongoing Conference of Arab Ministers of Water and
Agriculture, which opened here today.
</P>
<P>
Egypt is keen on participating in all forms of unified Arab
actions whose aims are to benefit the supreme interests of our
Arab nation and the welfare of the international community, he
said in the message, read out on his behalf by Youssef Wali,
deputy premier and minister of agriculture.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak said Arab countries should step up joint Arab
investment ventures in river development and further research and
studies on means of rationalizing the use of water.
</P>
<P>
They should also abide by agreements on the use of waters by
countries that share the same river basins and take all necessary
measures that protect and preserve water resources, he added.
</P>
<P>
The two-day conference of Arab ministers of water and
agriculture is jointly organized by the Arab Organization for
Agricultural Development and the Egyptian Ministry of Agriculture
and Land Reclamation.
</P>
<P>
The conference is attended by Arab League Assistant Secretary
General Abdel Rahman al-Sihbani, Chairman of the Arab
Organization for Agricultural Development Yehia Bakour, Arab
ministers of agriculture and representatives from Arab and
international organizations.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a recent study has showed that the scarity of water
and the indifference to the issue has blocked the agricultural
development in the Arab world that lies in the desert belt over
the equatorial zone.
</P>
<P>
The study, the work of the General Secretariat of the Union of
Arab Chamber, cautioned against the negative impact of the
limited water resources on future plans for self-sufficiency in
cereals.
</P>
<P>
About 80 percent of water in the Arab world is used in
agriculture and the rate goes even higher in countries like
Egypt, Iraq, Morocco, Oman, Saudi Arabia and Yemen.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank has predicted that the per capita quota of
fresh water in the Mideast and North Africa per year will
nosedive from 3,300 to 650 cubic meters over the period from 1960
to 2025.
</P>
<P>
By then, the Arab states will have to settle with two thirds
of the amount used by Asian or seven times less than the
international average. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
