<HEADLINE> Taiwan Not Qualified to Join World Health Organization </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 29 (Xinhua) -- Taiwan, as one of China's
provinces, is not qualified to join the World Health Organization
(WHO), Chinese Foreign Ministry Spokesman Cui Tiankai said here
today.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on a report that a Latin American nation is to
prepare to propose that Taiwan join the WHO, Cui said that since
the United Nations and its special organs are inter-governmental
international organizations, only sovereign states can apply for
entry.
</P>
<P>
Cui noted that the raising of Taiwan's representation in the
WHO under any pretext and in any form, is an open attempt to
create "two Chinas" or "one China, one Taiwan" in the WHO, and
constitutes a severe infringement upon China's sovereignty and
territorial integrity and a wanton interference in its internal
affairs.
</P>
<P>
"The Chinese government and people will never tolerate it," he
stressed.
</P>
<P>
"The WHO's position on this issue is clear and consistent," he
noted, "We appreciate this and believe that a large number of
countries in the WHO can hold justice and safeguard the purposes
and principles of both the UN Charter and the WHO's by-laws.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
