<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Macao Police Action Applauded </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, April 29 (Xinhua) -- Macao police's unprecedented move
Monday targeting heads of organized crimes have won local praises
although they failed to seize the targets.
</P>
<P>
Local newspapers gave big coverage to the police action which
started at six o'clock Monday and lasted seven hours. About 100
policemen raided 15 household units where gangland heads were
believed to live, taking away documents, two cars and a large
amount of contraband cigarettes.
</P>
<P>
"Although the target suspects were missed and crime cases
remain uncracked, the actions show the determination of the police
 departments in fighting crimes," said a commentary in today's
Macao Daily News.
</P>
<P>
It said that the actions demonstrate the police are launching
an active attack on triads, which is "a positive sign."
</P>
<P>
The action is the second within a week by local police
departments to deter a wave of crimes that have claimed 10 deaths
and a dozen injuries since the beginning of the year.
</P>
<P>
"The two consecutive actions demonstrate the earnest
determination of security authorities in cracking down on
organized crimes," the Va Kio Newspaper said in a commentary
today. "It is in line with the demand of the public."
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for the Police Action Coordination Center said
late Monday that the center will make further investigation into
the seized documents and cars, and promised to step up efforts to
ensure safety and public order.  
</P>
</TEXT>
