<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chemical Arms Pact Takes Effect </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, April 29 (Xinhua) -- The convention banning the
development, production, stockpiling and use of chemical weapons
entered into force today.
</P>
<P>
The Chemical Weapons Convention (CWC) is the first
multilaterally negotiated disarmament instrument which bans an
entire category of weapons of mass destruction in a verifiable
manner.
</P>
<P>
The treaty also requires member states to destroy their
chemical weapons stockpiles and production facilities within a
specified period. The goal is to eliminate such weapons by 2007.
</P>
<P>
Up to now, 165 states have signed the treaty which was
finalized in 1993 after more than 10 years of negotiations.
Eighty-seven countries have ratified it before the 29 April
deadline.
</P>
<P>
China ratified the convention last December and submitted the
letter of ratification to the United Nations Friday to become one
of the signatory states to the CWC.
</P>
<P>
Among the five permanent Security Council members, France,
Britain, the United States and China have ratified the treaty,
leaving Russia the only one yet to do so.
</P>
<P>
The First Conference of State Parties to the CWC will be opened
by U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan on May 6 in the Hague, the
Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
On the occasion, an organization for the prohibition of
chemical weapons will be formally formed.
</P>
<P>
It is learned the organization plans to have 140 inspectors and
visit about 100 chemical-arms sites. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
