<HEADLINE> Nigeria to Host Africa's First Ladies Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, April 29 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria is to host the inaugural
summit of Africa's first Ladies Peace Mission between May 5 and 7
in capital Abuja.
</P>
<P>
Malam Masir, chief press secretary to Nigerian First Lady
Mariam Sani Abacha, announced on Monday that most of the invited
guests had agreed to attend the summit personally or send
representatives.
</P>
<P>
The summit is organized jointly by the Organization of African
Unity (OAU), Economic Commission for Africa and secretariat of
the Africa Peace Mission which is temporarily based in Abuja.
</P>
<P>
Nigerian Head of State General Sani Abach will be the special
guest of honor and are expected to declare the summit open.
</P>
<P>
Maryam Abacha will deliver the keynote address while
Secretary-General of the United Nations, Kofi Annan,
Secretary-General of the OAU, Salim Ahmed Salim, and leaders of
other international agencies are expected to attend the meeting.
</P>
<P>
The summit is expected to examine the role the first ladies
would play towards resolving conflicts on the African continent.
</P>
<P>
The Committee of the African First Ladies Peace Mission was
established at the Fourth International Conference on Women held
in Beijing, China in November 1995 and Maryam Abacha was
appointed to lead to committee. 
</P>
</TEXT>
