<HEADLINE> Thai Firm to Set up Joint Industrial Zone in Myanmar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, April 29 (Xinhua) -- A Thai company has concluded a
contract with Myanmar's housing development authority to jointly
set up an international standard industrial zone in Yangon,
capital of Myanmar.
</P>
<P>
The contract to establish the zone in Hlaingthaya area was
signed here Monday between the Rojana Industrial Park Public Co.
Ltd. of Thailand and the Department of Human Settlement and
Housing Development of the Myanmar Ministry of Construction,
according to today's official paper The New Light of Myanmar.
</P>
<P>
The industrial zone will be the third foreign-invested one in
Myanmar after Thanlyin-Kyauktan and Mingaladon being set up by
Singapore's Sinmardev International Pte Ltd. and Japan's Mitsui
Co. Ltd. respectively.
</P>
<P>
The Thai company will invest 14 million U.S. dollars for the
infrastructure and development cost whereas the Myanmar department
will offer the rights of use of land as its share, the report
said.
</P>
<P>
The area for the first phase will be about 101 hectares and the
construction period is two years, to be followed by the second
phase with another 81 hectares, the report added.
</P>
<P>
In Hlaingthaya area, some multi-national foreign companies have
been involved in setting up dairy products, galvanized iron sheet,
 sanitary products and garment factories.
</P>
<P>
Thailand's investment in Myanmar ranks third after Britain and
Singapore with 1.02 billion U.S. dollars in 39 projects at the end
of March this year, according to official statistics.  
</P>
</TEXT>
