<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyprus to Protest Against Turkish Cypriots' Limit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, April 29 (Xinhua) -- The Cypriot government will
make representations to the U.N. over the attitude of the Turkish
Cypriot northern side regarding a scheduled visit by Greek
Cypriots to perform pilgrimage at the Turkish-controlled part of
the island.
</P>
<P>
The visit was planned to have taken place Sunday, the Easter,
for Greek Cypriots to visit the Monastery of Apostolos Andreas,
but was canceled by the government Saturday following Turkish
Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash's insistence on censoring the list
of visitors.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish Cypriots also asked to limit the proposed number
of Greek Cypriot visitors from 800 to 600 and rejected the
entry to journalists.
</P>
<P>
U.N. Spokesman in Cyprus Waldemar Rokoszewski has expressed
regret for the outcome and hoped there will be more willingness
in the future.
</P>
<P>
Cypriot Foreign Minister Yiannakis Cassoulides said today that
representations will be made to U.N. officials in the island state
and to the U.N. headquarters in New York as well.
</P>
<P>
On April 19, some 450 Turkish Cypriots crossed to the
government-controlled southern areas and prayed at the Hala
Sultan Tekke, one of the holiest Muslim places of worship in the
world, near the southeastern coastal town of Larnaca.
</P>
<P>
The Move was regarded as a good-will gesture taken by the
Greek Cypriot side following a U.N.-led six-week proximity talks
between the Greek and Turkish Cypriots, which were aimed at
paving the way for face-to-face negotiations between leaders of
the two communities by the middle of this year.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into the Greek Cypriot south and
Turkish Cypriot north since 1974 when Turkish troops occupied
the northern third of the island in the wake of an Athens-backed
coup. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
