<HEADLINE> Drug Trafficking, Fraud on Rise in Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 29 (Xinhua) -- Drug trafficking and commercial
fraud are on the increase in Kenya during recent years since the
liberalization of economy, local newspaper the Daily Nation
reported today.
</P>
<P>
It said customs officers at the Jomo Kenyatta International
Airport in Nairobi and the Mombasa Port seized more than 20 tons
of drugs between October 1995 and August 1996.
</P>
<P>
Kenya Revenue Authority Commissioner General Yusuf Nzibo was
quoted as saying here on Tuesday that drug trafficking was
featured with greater sophistication since the advent of
liberalization.
</P>
<P>
In July 1996, customs officers at the airport seized 2.9 kms
of heroin which was stuffed in large buttons sewn on ladies'
clothes.
</P>
<P>
He told an ongoing drugs control seminar attended by
representatives of 15 countries in Nairobi that commercial fraud
just as drug trafficking has also been on the increase during the
recent years.
</P>
<P>
The Kenyan official noted that travel documents such as
passports were made with sophisticated machines imported into the
country.
</P>
<P>
Nzibo called for a regional approach to help combat the two
evils which, he said, would wreck the local economies and
potential human resources. 
</P>
</TEXT>
