<HEADLINE> Fuel Supply Still Low in Zambia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, April 29 (Xinhua) -- Zambia spent more than 126
billion Kwacha (about one billion U.S. Dollars) from January 1996
to March this year on importing crude oil, but fuel supply is
still low, adversely affecting the country's mining industry.
</P>
<P>
According to the real sector data report from the Financial
Ministry, most of the money went to Saudi Arabia that supplied 61
percent of the oil.
</P>
<P>
The total amount spent on crude oil represents nearly nine
percent of the current national budget.
</P>
<P>
The mining industry was and is still the most affected as the
short supply of high fuel adversely affected copper production in
the past two months.
</P>
<P>
The report, however, said the supply of petroleum products is
expected to be improved by the end of June after the maintenance
work is carried out in the refinery in the north of Zambia and
the ongoing rehabilitation of the Tazama Pipeline is finished.
</P>
</TEXT>
