<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Muslim Rebels Deny Hand in Hotel Fire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 29 (Xinhua) -- A Philippine Muslim rebel group
today denied being involved in a hotel fire which killed 27 people
in the southern city of Cotabato on April 26.
</P>
<P>
Ghadzali Jaafar, Moro Islamic Liberation Front (MILF) deputy
chief for political affairs, also denied the group has a hand in
the kidnapping of an airline executive in Cotabato the same day,
the Philippine News Agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
Local media reports earlier quoted Interior and Local
Government Secretary Robert Barbers as saying the MILF has a hand
in the latest two tragic incidents.
</P>
<P>
The reports said that the hotel burning which also injured 11
others, was part of a MILF campaign to sabotage the state of the
region address by Nur Misuari, governor of the Autonomous Region
in Muslim Mindanao.
</P>
<P>
The address was originally set on April 28 but was postponed by
Misuari as an expression of sympathy to the fire victims, among
whom were members of the Moro National Liberation Front (MNLF) who
were at the hotel to attend the address.
</P>
<P>
Jaafar said certain groups are only trying to promote animosity
between the MILF and the MNLF as both are engaged in the peace
process in Mindanao.
</P>
<P>
The MILF leader also disclaimed responsibility in the
kidnapping of Fernando Mandanas, branch manager of the Philippine
Airlines in Cotabato city.
</P>
<P>
The abduction took place Saturday evening while the police were
preoccupied with the aftermath of the hotel fire.
</P>
<P>
Witnesses claimed Mandanas was abducted by seven armed men who
identified themselves as policemen.
</P>
<P>
"I want to put this on record. Officially, the MILF is not
involved and has no knowledge of the kidnapping (of Mandanas) and
all other kidnappings," Jaafar said.
</P>
<P>
Jaafar charged, "Maybe before an incident takes place, the
authorities already have a prepared list of who should be blamed."
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
