<DOCNO> XIE19970429.0164 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Largest Steel Manufacturer A Shining Example for State-Owned Enterprises (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, April 29 (Xinhua) -- Baoshan Steel and Iron (Group)
Co. (Baosteel), China's most productive manufacturer of steel
products, became the leading money-maker in the metallurgical
industry, setting a sterling example for China's state-owned
enterprises to follow.
</P>
<P>
Located in the suburbs of Shanghai, the group with a state
investment of 30 billion yuan now has an annual producing capacity
of 6.5 million tons of steel, 6.71 million tons of iron, and
500,000 tons of seamless steel tubes.
</P>
<P>
Through the large-scale importation of advanced technology and
strict control of employment, the 1,300-strong group has raised
its productivity to 655 tons of steel per capita annually, which
is much higher than the industry's average.
</P>
<P>
Li Ming, chairman of Baosteel, attributed such rapid
development to the group's courageous reform of its enterprise
system.
</P>
<P>
Unlike other large and medium-sized state-owned enterprises,
the group has no "welfare facilities" such as hospital and schools
for employees' families. All its auxiliary businesses, including
the equipment maintenance, are separated from the mother company.
</P>
<P>
And the group relocates about 2,000 workers to its subsidiaries
every year, in order to make room for technological renovation.
</P>
<P>
As a result, the group, which is now the top steel maker with
the smallest number of workers in China, developed quickly while
some of the country's major steel factories fell into heavy debts.
</P>
<P>
According to the chairman, Baosteel generated sales revenues of
27.22 billion yuan, and turned over 4.97 billion yuan in profits
and taxes in 1996, when the domestic market was severely affected
by foreign steel products and the benefits of the whole industry
generally shrank. Meanwhile, the group's foreign currency earnings
stood at 465 million US dollars, maintaining a leading position in
the industry.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970429.0165 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Largest Steel Manufacturer A Shining Example for State-Owned Enterprises (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Industrial analysts said that the fast growth of Baosteel was
also driven by the technological advantage formed by 19 years of
heavy input since the group was founded.
</P>
<P>
So far, Baosteel has developed 195 new products and 569 items
of technical breakthroughs, which achieved direct economic
benefits totalling 14.8 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
Baosteel's economic miracle is highlighted by its advanced
operation system which combined both the experience of foreign
steel giants and the particular situation of China.
</P>
<P>
In the group, the administrative functions are concentrated in
the top managing board, with each operation procedure looked after
by a special functional organ. This operation system successfully
avoided such chaos prevalent in other state-owned enterprises
where the power is decentralized and any important decision is
hard to make in a short time.
</P>
<P>
To acquire more competitivity in overseas markets, Baosteel
announced an ambitious expansion project to increase steel
manufacturing capacity by 4.29 million tons annually, and iron by
3.25 million tons. The combined producing capacity of the group
will reach 11 million tons of steel by the end of this century.
</P>
<P>
Zheng Haihang, research fellow of Chinese Academy of Social
Sciences, said that the new round of growth, which followed the
national economy's soft landing last year, will offer a "very
favorable external conditions" to those Chinese enterprises taking
the lead in structural reform and readjusting the product mix.
</P>
<P>
The prosperity of such enterprises as Baosteel augurs a bright
future as the country's painstaking reform in the state-owned
sectors enters a crucial phase, said Chen Qingtai, vice-minister
of the State Economic and Trade Commission.
</P>
<P>
The experience achieved by Baosteel and other profitable
companies can be used as a good reference for thousands of
state-owned enterprises running at a loss in the country, Chen
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
