<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Northeast Chinese City Involved In American Farming </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, April 29 (Xinhua) -- Haicheng City, in Liaoning
Province has spent 200,000 U.S. dollars on a piece of farmland in
New York State as part of China's comprehensive reform drive.
</P>
<P>
Local sources say that the city has sent representatives to the
newly-established "Haicheng Village" in Jamestown, New York, and
that they are busy preparing operations there. It will also be a
way to help products from Haicheng to enter the U.S. market.
</P>
<P>
Haicheng, which has been rated high in economic development, is
only one of several Chinese cities involved in such ventures.
</P>
<P>
Last August, when local officials made an inspection tour of
New York State, they found that Jamestown, which is near the
Canadian border and very close to Niagara Falls, had the advantage
of preferential policies for foreign nationals and low land costs.
</P>
<P>
After studying and discussing the situation, they made the
decision to buy the 86.67-hectare parcel of land from a private
business. The move was welcomed by Jamestown and resulted in the
establishment of cooperative ties between the two cities.
</P>
<P>
According to the sources, Jamestown has also decided to put six
million U.S. dollars annually into support for construction work
at "Haicheng Village" and to provide a certain amount in loans.
</P>
<P>
The two cities have also signed a five-year contract for a
training program under which each city will send 30 students to
the other city for special training.
</P>
<P>
Jamestown has already started eight investment ventures in
Haicheng City, one of which, a joint venture in rubber production,
has begun operation.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
