<HEADLINE> Egyptian FM Leaves for Djibouti </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 29 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr
Moussa left here this morning for Djibouti, starting a six-day
tour to four East African countries to promote bilateral ties and
boost investment.
</P>
<P>
He will deliver messages from Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak
to the leaders of Djibouti, Tanzania, Kenya and Uganda.
</P>
<P>
Moussa, accompanied by a team of Egyptian businessmen and
officials from the ministries of agriculture, irrigation and
economy, will discuss ways with the host countries to expanded the
scope of investment.
</P>
<P>
A number of joint projects will be inaugurated during the
tour, said the top Egyptian diplomat on the eve of his visit.
</P>
<P>
Egypt has put its expertise at the disposal of Tanzania, Kenya
and Uganda as regards the issue of using the Nile River water,
according to Egyptian Ambassador to Tanzania Mohamed Rafik Khalil.
</P>
<P>
Egypt, Tanzania, Kenya and Uganda and six other Nile basin
countries share the river for drinking water.
</P>
<P>
During his visit to Uganda, the last stop of his tour, Moussa
will complete the talks that started in Cairo during the Ugandan
President Yoweri Museveni's two-day visit here over the last
weekend.
</P>
<P>
During the tour, Moussa will also continue the political
consultations between Egypt and the four countries on the
developments of the situation in the Horn of Africa and the Great
Lakes region.
</P>
<P>
Egypt has denied charges that it has any military presence in
any of the Great Lake countries that have been plagued by years of
ethnic war and flood of refugees.
</P>
<P>
The Great Lakes region includes Burundi, Rwanda, Zaire,
Uganda and Tanzania. 
</P>
</TEXT>
