<HEADLINE> Australia, Japan to Promote Defense Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, April 29 (Xinhua) -- Australia and Japan today agreed
to promote their defense relationship, and which, they considered,
should be part of the two countries' bilateral association.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a joint news conference, Australian Prime Minister
John Howard and visiting Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto
were careful to avoid suggestions that defense ties should be
placed on the same level as those of the two countries with the
U.S.
</P>
<P>
Hashimoto, who arrived here Monday on a two-day visit, said
both countries should promote further cooperation on security
issues through senior level political and military consultations.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders agreed on an annual prime ministerial summit
and announced a visit to Japan by Australian Defense Minister Ian
McLachlan later this year.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese leader confirmed that his country would support
Australia's bid for involvement in the Asia-Europe Meeting (ASEM)
forum. "Concerning Australia's participation in ASEM, I expressed
Japan's continued support for the new membership of Australia,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
Hashimoto also told the news conference that he and John Howard
had agreed to further promote cooperation between Australian and
Japan in the World Trade Organization (WHO).
</P>
<P>
He confirmed the two nations would make efforts to realize the
accession of China to the WHO.  
</P>
</TEXT>
