<HEADLINE> S'pore Workers Called on to Keep up Republic's Success </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, April 29 (Xinhua) -- Acting Prime Minister Lee Hsien
Loong called on Singapore workers and their families today to work
together to keep up the Singapore success story.
</P>
<P>
In his May Day message, Lee noted that while Singapore had a
credible economic performance last year, it also highlighted the
country's vulnerability. As a small and open economy, Singapore
could do well only when external demand is healthy, he said.
</P>
<P>
When global demand slowed and business cycles were down,
Singapore would be affected more quickly and severely than others,
he noted, adding that Singapore relied on free trade and
investments but this also means keener competition.
</P>
<P>
He emphasized that although the government wanted Singaporeans
to earn good wages, to justify the premium, workers must have
better technical skills and be more productive than workers
elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
In this regard, the acting prime minister noted that trade
unions were pushing hard for more worker training and that
training programs were being well subscribed.
</P>
<P>
Last year, about 466,000 workers received Skills Development
Fund training, up from 356,000 in 1990.
</P>
<P>
Lee urged workers to do more training as, he said, the payoff
to workers for the investment of time and effort in continuous
self-improvement is higher incomes and better job security.
</P>
</TEXT>
