<HEADLINE> S'pore to Cooperate with Myanmar in Fishery Sector </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, April 29 (Xinhua) -- A Singaporean agro-business
mission led by Director of Primary Production Department of the
Ministry of National Development George Tay has had discussions
with Myanmar Minister for Livestock and Fisheries U Aung Thaung on
cooperation in the sector of fishery.
</P>
<P>
The discussion, which was held here Monday, included processing
of Myanmar's marine resources, establishment of cold storages, ice
factories and fish powder factories, raising of poultry, mutual
cooperation and exchange of techniques for development of meat and
fisheries sector, according to today's official paper The New
Light of Myanmar.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar exploited about 590,000 tons of marine products
annually in the past few years out of the maximum sustainable
yield which is estimated at about 1.05 million tons per year.
</P>
<P>
Foreign companies investing in Myanmar's fishery sector have
reportedly come from Thailand, China, Japan and Bangladesh, which
have formed joint ventures with the country's state-run fishery
enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Total foreign investment in livestock breeding and fisheries
sector had reached 269.54 million U.S. dollars in 17 permitted
projects by the end of March this year, according to the latest
official statistics.  
</P>
