<HEADLINE> Nyerere Urges International Support to EAC </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, April 29 (Xinhua) -- Former Tanzanian President
Julius Nyerere has urged the international community to fund the
East African Co-operation (EAC) to facilitate its development
plans, local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
Nyerere made the call in Arusha, northern Tanzania on Sunday
during the opening of the German-East Africa Dialogue, saying
that the group needs financial support.
</P>
<P>
"When external finance is required, I hope it will be advanced
generously especially for infrastructure which helps the
profitability of other investments," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Unless it exists, it may be impossible to attract private
foreign investment in any sector. Yet infrastructure will not
itself be financially profitable if the original capital costs
are so heavy that potential users can not afford to use it," he
added.
</P>
<P>
He told the participants in the dialogue from Kenya, Uganda,
Tanzania and Germany that East Africans are eager to forge strong
unity.
</P>
<P>
"We in East Africa are asking the international community,
with special reference to Europe, to help us in our modest
initial plans to integrate our economies," he said.
</P>
<P>
Nyerere stressed the need for the regional grouping to be
given technical assistance or experienced advisers to hasten
progress.
</P>
<P>
He said though East Africa is certainly much better off than
it was in 1967 when the first East African Community established,
regarding highly educated and technically trained personnel, the
region still needs assistance in that field.
</P>
<P>
The three-day dialogue was organized by the Friedrich Ebert
Stiftung in collaboration with the German Science and Research
Foundation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
