<HEADLINE> China, U.S. Agree to Further Develop Relationship </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 28 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Vice Premier and
Foreign Minister Qian Qichen and U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright agreed to further develop the Sino-U.S relationship in
their talks held here today.
</P>
<P>
Albright's successful visit to China in February made a good
beginning for this year's continuing development of the bilateral
relations, a Chinese spokesman quoted Qian as saying at a press
conference after the talks.
</P>
<P>
Qian hoped that his visit to Washington would keep and
strengthen the momentum of high-level dialogue between the two
countries, so that the relationship could be further developed.
</P>
<P>
Qian left for Washington from Moscow Saturday after the end of
his trip accompanying Chinese President Jiang Zemin's state visit
to Russia.
</P>
<P>
Albright, who visited Beijing early this year during her maiden
foreign trip as the first woman U.S. state secretary, said that
developing the relationship between Washington and Beijing is a
priority on the U.S. government's agenda.
</P>
<P>
Albright hoped the two countries would enlarge the volume of
trade. Qian said that China is willing to open its market wider to
U.S. high-tech products like aircraft and communication equipment.
</P>
<P>
Qian said that he hoped that the United States would remove the
trade barriers it has erected and make efforts to promote economic
and trade cooperation between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. secretary said that she will happily attend the
ceremony marking the return of Hong Kong to China on July 1, said
the spokesman. 
</P>
</TEXT>
