<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-29 07:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey Sends 400 Soldiers to Iraq's Northern </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, April 29 (Xinhua) -- The Turkish army dispatched some
400 soldiers to assist a projected Peace Monitoring Force (PMF)
consisting of Iraqi Turkmens and Assyrians on the cease-fire
line in northern Iraq, local newspaper Daily News reported
today.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted senior Turkish military officials, who
declined to be named, as saying that the Turkish soldiers
travelled to the region last week in armored vehicles, and
military stations consisting of small armed units would be set up
along the cease-fire line to collect information about the
situation in the area.
</P>
<P>
Turkey decided to increase the strength of the force from 200
to 400 because the cease-fire line is very long and a force of 200
is not enough. "But the Turkmens and Assyrians are to work for the
PMF, not Turkish soldiers," Daily News quoted a foreign ministry
official as saying.
</P>
<P>
The first PMF group of 50 Turkmens, which was deployed in
northern Iraq last week, has begun its mission in the region in a
bid to supervise the truce between the two Iraqi-Kurdish rivals,
the Kurdistan Democratic Party (KDP) and the Patriotic Union of
Kurdistan (PUK), according to the semi-official Anatolia News
Agency Monday.
</P>
<P>
The agency said that the deployment of all the 180 Turkmens
and 20 Assyrians was expected to be completed within the
following weeks.
</P>
<P>
The KDP and PUK agreed to the establishment of the PMF last
February in the third round of the peace talks held in Ankara
jointly sponsored by the United States, Britain and Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Last January, representatives from Turkey, the U.S. and
Britain met with three Iraqi delegations, the KDP, the PUK and
the Turkmen Front, to review progress in implementing the
principles agreed on October 31 and November 15 last year.
</P>
<P>
Turkey, supporting Iraq's Turkmen minority because of ethnic
and cultural bonds, wants the Kurds to have a say in the
administration of the area.
</P>
<P>
The KDP, backed by Iraqi President Saddam Hussein, fought
against the Iranian-backed PUK in late August last year, during
which the U.S. launched air strikes against Iraqi military
targets.
</P>
<P>
The northern part of Iraq has been occupied by the two Kurdish
groups since the Gulf War in 1991, but it split into rival zones
after the KDP and the PUK began fighting each other in 1994.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970429.0185 </DOCNO>
