<HEADLINE> European Bank Finances Kenya's Small Enterprises </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 29 (Xinhua) -- The European Investment Bank has
agreed to provide some 60 million U.S. Dollars to support the
development of small and medium enterprises in Kenya, according
to a Daily Nation report today.
</P>
<P>
The loan is the third line of credit under the Global Private
Enterprises (GPE) program run by the European bank.
</P>
<P>
The paper said the loan is given to enterprises which have
invested in the agro-industrial, manufacturing, horticultural,
floriculture, fishing, fish-processing, mining, quarrying and
tourism sectors.
</P>
<P>
The investments to be financed may relate to new projects,
modernization, restructuring, expansion and diversification of
existing activities, it added.
</P>
<P>
The loan has brought the GPE facility in the east African
country to l30 million Dollars since 1992, which has already
benefited many enterprises such as horticultural projects in
Nairobi, Nakuru, Eldoret and agro-industry projects in Athi
River.
</P>
<P>
Between 1995 and 1996, about 70 enterprises were financed by
the GPE facility and more than half of the facility went to
ventures which are primarily foreign exchange earners.
</P>
<P>
The various investments by the facility are estimated to
create employment for about 4,000 people in the country where
there are about 35 percent unemployment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
