<HEADLINE> Security Situation in N. Uganda Improved </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, April 29 (Xinhua) -- Security situation in northern
Uganda improved as rebel were defeated in the region, Uganda
President Yoweri Museveni told the parliament yesterday.
</P>
<P>
According to "the New Vision" today, the president reaffirmed
that he will not talk to Joseph Kony, leader fo the Lord's
Resistance Army (LRA) rebels.
</P>
<P>
"The remnants of Kony's group have broken into small groups
that are being picked one by one or surrendering in droves," he
said.
</P>
<P>
LRA is a rebel group acting in northern Uganda and has bases
in southern Sudan. It suffered a series of defeat both in its
fightings against the government troops in northern Uganda and
Sudan People's Liberation Army (SPLA) in southern Sudan.
</P>
<P>
Uganda's government troops on Monday displayed 80 LRA rebels
and 114 Sudanese soldiers captured earlier this month. Michael
Ongom, one of the captured LRA rebel, said they had tried to set
up a base within the territory of Uganda.
</P>
<P>
Apart from LRA, there were another two main rebel groups in
Uganda: the West Nile Bank Front (WNBF) acting in northwestern
Uganda and having bases in southern Sudan, and the Allied
Democratic Forces (ADF) acting in western Uganda and having bases
in east Zaire.
</P>
<P>
WNBF lost its main forces last month in its fightings against
SPLA in southern Sudan and against the government troops in
northwestern Uganda. Joseph Awara, a WNBF commander who
surrendered last month with 60 rebels, said he was treated well
since he reported to local authorities.
</P>
<P>
Major Tom Butime, Ugandan Minister of Internal Affairs, urged
ADF rebels to surrender, saying that the rebels have no chance to
stay in war-torn Zaire.
</P>
<P>
According to captives released last week, ADF was divided into
two small warring groups in the wake of several defeats in its
battle against Zairean rebels led by Laurent Kabila. ADF lost 30
soldiers in a fighting on Monday against the government troops in
Uganda's western Kasese district. 
</P>
</TEXT>
