<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Emblem and Mascot Chosen for 1999 World Philatelic Exhibition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 29 (Xinhua) -- The Great Wall and a "Jade Hare"
have been chosen as emblem and mascot for the World Philatelic
Exhibition, which will be held in China in 1999.
</P>
<P>
The stamps' perforations are used for the battlements of the
Great Wall and the date appears in the shape of clouds above the
wall.
</P>
<P>
Designers say that the three "9s" are rose-colored on a green
background, like flower buds, indicating that the friendship of
Chinese people will be communicated to the rest of the world by
the stamps.
</P>
<P>
Because 1999 is the year of the hare, the Jade Hare, a
character from Chinese fairy tales that lives in the moon, was
chosen as the mascot. Shang Dynasty (16-11th Century BC) bronzes
and Han Dynasty (206 BC-220 AD) hare-shaped jades were models for
the design.
</P>
<P>
The emblem and the mascot were designed by Yan Yunfu and Liu
Jude, professors with the Central Institute of Arts and
Crafts. They were chosen from 1,932 design entries from all over
China. The youngest designer was eight years old and the oldest 79.
</P>
<P>
The World Philatelic Exhibition will be held in the China
International Exhibition Center from August 21 to 30, 1999, and
will show 3,500 sets of stamps in two categories: for competition
and for display.
</P>
<P>
The organizers have planned an international forum on stamp
collection and activities to promote stamp collection among young
people.
</P>
<P>
The exhibition will have a special hall for sale of stamps and
a post office that will use a special postmark. 
</P>
</TEXT>
