<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Heart Transplantee Survives Record 5 Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 29 (Xinhua) -- A Chinese man who received a
heart transplant has set a record in China for organ transplants
by surviving five years.
</P>
<P>
"Although heart transplants are no longer a difficult operation
overseas and many transplant recipients have lived for more than
10 years, the five-year record is still meaningful in China where
organ transplants are still behind the times," according to a
report in "People's Daily" overseas edition.
</P>
<P>
Yang Yumin was diagnosed as suffering from acute heart disease
and doctors at the No.2 Hospital of Harbin Medical University did
a heart transplant operation on April 26, 1992.
</P>
<P>
They then had to get him through near-fatal post-operative
complications, such as hemorrhaging, a rejection of the organ by
his body, and infection.
</P>
<P>
For the past four years he has had regular physical check-ups
and a steady diet of drugs to help his new heart function normally.
</P>
<P>
Yang, who is now 40, runs a grocery store with his wife in
northeast China's Harbin City. He even got a daughter three years
ago when his wife gave birth to a baby girl.
</P>
<P>
The hospital performed two more heart transplant operations:
one on a 34-year-old middle school teacher in February of 1994,
and the other on a 49-year-old worker in November of 1995. These
operations were also successful and both persons have been able to
work again, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
Chinese doctors have also been successful in performing kidney,
liver, and lung transplant. Surgeons at Beijing's Anzhen Hospital
performed a successful lung transplant 26 months ago. It was said
that this marks another breakthrough in organ transplants in
China. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
