<DOCNO> XIE19970429.0202 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South China To Use Japanese Solar Technology For Housing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANNING, April 29 (Xinhua) -- South China's Guangxi Zhuang
Autonomous Region will use Japanese solar energy technology for
residential buildings in Nanning, its capital.
</P>
<P>
The Guangxi Academy of Sciences' Institute of Applied Physics
signed an agreement with Japan's Om Taiyo Association in March on
solar energy housing in Japanese and Chinese styles for the city.
</P>
<P>
Guangxi has longer periods of sunlight than in northern parts
of China.
</P>
<P>
A Japanese expert explains that solar batteries on the roof of
a house collect solar energy providing heating through pipes in
winter. In summer, the same pipes remove hot air from the house
and the hot water can be used for bathing.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese solar energy houses use 33 percent less energy
than other forms of air conditioning and are good for
environmental protection.
</P>
<P>
He Jiang, deputy director of the institute, said that the city
plans to use the technology for medium-height buildings, the most
popular buildings in the city.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
