<HEADLINE> North China City Recovers Quickly from Earthquake (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HOHHOT, April 29 (Xinhua) -- Earthquake-stricken Baotou, the
largest industrial city in north China's Inner Mongolia Autonomous
Region, has made progress in returning to a normal life after
being hit by a severe earthquake on May 3 of last year.
</P>
<P>
The quake caused more than four billion yuan (about 482 million
US dollars) of damages. It also left 400,000 people homeless, but
Vice-Mayor Zhao Shuanglian told Xinhua, "With a year's hard work
we've made great progress in building apartment buildings and
houses, schools, hospitals, and infrastructure."
</P>
<P>
The city has repaired or rebuilt 3.45 million sq.m. of housing
and will add two million sq.m. more this year, providing 12
sq.m. of living space for everyone.
</P>
<P>
The city has rebuilt or repaired 720,000 sq.m. of school rooms
and 193,000 sq.m. of hospital rooms.
</P>
<P>
Last year, it spent 80 million yuan repairing water, heat, and
gas pipelines.
</P>
</TEXT>
