<HEADLINE> Israel Eases Closure on West Bank, Gaza </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 29 (Xinhua) -- The Israeli army today eased
a total closure imposed on the West Bank and Gaza Strip,
allowing a limited number of Palestinians to enter Israel.
</P>
<P>
According to an Israel Radio report, from this morning, more
than 5,000 married Palestinian traders and hotel workers who are
over 30 are being permitted entry into the Jewish state.
</P>
<P>
In addition, Palestinian medical personnel, teachers,
journalists, and employees of the Israeli Civil Administration,
international organizations and religious institutions may also
travel to Jerusalem from the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Last month, Israel imposed the total closure on the West Bank
and Gaza Strip immediately after a suicide bombing attack in a
downtown coffee shop in Tel Aviv, which left three Israeli women
dead and more than 50 others injured.
</P>
<P>
The closure has barred tens of thousands of Palestinians from
returning to their jobs inside Israel, and from traveling
between the West Bank and Gaza Strip.
</P>
<P>
Later, the Israeli army eased the closure, allowing Gaza
Strip residents in the West Bank to return to the strip, as well
as West Bank inhabitants in the Gaza Strip to travel home.
</P>
<P>
The army was also letting 20,000 Palestinian workers enter
Israel, but the permit then was only to be issued to
married men over the age of 45.
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, another 22 Palestinian ambulances were allowed to
enter Israel on an emergency basis, bringing to 36 the number
of ambulances permitted to go into Israel from the Palestinian
autonomous areas.
</P>
<P>
However, before the week-long Jewish Passover holiday which
started last Monday, the Israeli army once again tightened the
closure on the West Bank and Gaza Strip, barring Palestinians from
entering the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
