<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-29 07:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> International Monitors to Meet on Israeli, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, April 29 (Xinhua) -- A five-nation committee
monitoring the cease-fire in south Lebanon is to hold a meeting
later today to discuss two complaints respectively filed by
Israel and Lebanon against each other.
</P>
<P>
Representatives from France, Israel, Lebanon, Syria and the
United States will start the meeting at the headquarters of the
U.N. peacekeeping force in the south Lebanese border town of
Naqoura at 11:00 a.m. (08:00 GMT) today.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon filed a complaint to the cease-fire monitoring
committee after a school bus packed with children was hit by
Israeli fire at the weekend.
</P>
<P>
The bus was hit with six 12.7 mm bullets fired from a position
manned by Israeli troops and their allied South Lebanon Army
(SLA) militia on the Kawkaba hilltop in the Israeli
self-proclaimed "security zone," Lebanese security sources said.
</P>
<P>
"Thank god, none of the students was hurt," bus driver Kamel
Madi, "I did my best to escape the fire."
</P>
<P>
"This is a blatant violation of the April 26 cease-fire
understanding because Israeli fire targeted a civilian target, a
school bus carrying students," sources in the Lebanese Foreign
Ministry said.
</P>
<P>
The same sources added that the Lebanese delegates to the
committee will present the panel with evidence proving Israel's
responsibility for the incident.
</P>
<P>
Under the truce agreement, which ended Israel's 17-day
offensive against Lebanon last year, Israeli troops and Lebanese
guerrillas are barred from targeting civilians or launching
attacks from civilian areas.
</P>
<P>
Jean-Michel Gaussot, the French chairman of the committee,
said the complaint will be made when the panel meets today to
discuss an Israeli protest earlier over an attack on an army
base inside northern Israel Friday by the fundamentalist
Lebanese guerrilla of Hezbollah, or Party of God.
</P>
<P>
General Amiram Levine, chief of Israel's northern military
command, described the shelling, which injured two soldiers, as
"a deliberate violation of the cease-fire reached last year
since this accord prohibits attacks on Israeli territory."
</P>
<P>
It was the first time Israel accused Hezbollah of firing
across the border since the end of Israel's Grapes of Wrath
Operation against the Shiite pro-Iranian Party of God in April
1996.
</P>
<P>
In a related development, the SLA-run Voice of the South
radio reported an Israeli threat to launch a new blitz against
Lebanon aimed at destroying Hezbollah and replacing the
cease-fire with another truce which is "more favorable" to the
Jewish state.
</P>
<P>
A Hezbollah source played down the threat, saying it was an
attempt to beef up morale among the Israeli troops and the SLA
militiamen.
</P>
<P>
"The threat is meant to be like vitamins to the Israeli
soldiers because their morale has decreased sharply following
Hezbollah's successful operations against them," the source
said.
</P>
<P>
Speaking on condition of anonymity, the source added that
Hezbollah "vows to destroy what is left of the SLA" and "will
not be stopped by Israeli threats which have proved to be
ineffective." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
