<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Number of Urban Poor in China Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 29 (Xinhua) -- Recent statistics from the State
Statistics Bureau show that China's population of poor people in
urban areas dropped to 11.76 million in 1996, a decline of 660,000
from 1995.
</P>
<P>
This came about because of projects to help the poor through
reemployment or establishing minimum living standards for urban
residents.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, 84 percent of the urban poor came from job changes or
unemployment resulting from economic restructuring. About 40
percent of these came from state-owned or collective firms,
especially in the coal, machinery, and textile sectors, which were
hard hit by reform measures.
</P>
<P>
Eighty-five percent of the poor also lived in economically
backward parts of the country in central and western regions.
</P>
<P>
The bureau says that the lives of these people are
deteriorating. In 1996, their per capita incomes dropped 12
percent to 1,321 yuan, equivalent to 30 percent of per capita
income for urban residents.
</P>
<P>
China set a poverty line for urban residents at a per capita
income of around 1,700 yuan. To help keep these people above the
poverty line, the country needs 4.2 billion yuan in relief funds
this year.
</P>
<P>
The bureau has also suggested poverty alleviation measures in
urban areas, that include increased investment in the central and
western parts of the country, adjusting income distribution, and
developing a social security system.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970429.0208 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-29 </DATE_TIME>
