<DOCNO> XIE19970429.0212 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IMF Endorses Gradual Current Account Liberalization </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 28 (Xinhua) -- The decision-making Interim
Committee of the International Monetary Fund (IMF) today issued a
communique, supporting orderly liberalization of member countries'
current account.
</P>
<P>
The communique, issued at the conclusion of the Interim
Committee's 48th meeting, stressed that an open and liberal system
of capital movements was beneficial to the world economy.
</P>
<P>
The committee considered the IMF uniquely placed to promote the
orderly liberalization of capital movements and to play a central
role in this effort.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, it agreed that the IMF's Articles should be amended
to make the promotion of current account liberalization a specific
purpose of the fund and to give it appropriate jurisdiction over
capital movements.
</P>
<P>
It said that the scope of such jurisdiction would need to be
carefully defined and sufficient flexibility should be allowed
through transitional provisions and approval policies.
</P>
<P>
The committee welcomed the generally favorable prospects for
the expansion of world output and trade, the communique noted.
</P>
<P>
Improved discipline in fiscal and monetary policies in many
countries has contributed to subdued or declining inflation and
relatively low long-term interest rates, it said.
</P>
<P>
The committee agreed that exchange rates should reflect
economic fundamentals and that the reemergence of large external
imbalances should be avoided. Excess volatility and significant
deviations from fundamentals are undesirable, it added.
</P>
<P>
Despite of the favorable situation and prospects, some
challenges remain, the communique noted. Among the advanced
economies, countries where growth has been relatively strong face
the challenge of sustaining the expansion while preventing a
possible upturn in inflation.
</P>
<P>
The committee agreed that the increasing globalization of
markets is an important force driving world growth and providing
opportunities to all countries. While globalization, it said, as
with other structural change, many adversely affect some segments
of society in the short run, the declining share of manufacturing
employment in advanced economies is primarily the consequence of
technical change rather than globalization.
</P>
<P>
It also expressed its backing for the action by the IMF
Executive Board to implement the fund's participation in the
Heavily Indebted Poor Countries (HIPC) Initiative through the
Enhanced Structural Adjustment Facility (ESAF) operations. The
ESAF is a concessional lending for developing countries which
undertake structural adjustment.
</P>
<P>
The committee is scheduled to meet again in Hong Kong on
September 21, this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970429.0213 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> East Chinese Province Prepares for Flood Season </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, April 29 (Xinhua) -- East China's Jiangsu Province,
which is on the lower reaches of China's largest river, the
Yangtze, is making preparations for possibly big flooding this
year.
</P>
<P>
An official with Flood Control Headquarters has urged people to
rid themselves of the idea of trusting to luck and to place
greater importance on relying on flood prevention.
</P>
<P>
Thirteen of Jiangsu's cities have worked out flood control
plans and the provincial government has spent 117 million yuan
(14.1 million US dollars) this year reinforcing river banks,
building a water diversion project and water works on the Wangyu
River, anti-flood projects, and 500 km of embankments along the
Yangtze River.
</P>
<P>
Another eight million yuan has been allocated for
flood-prevention materials, and the province has earmarked nine
million yuan for program-controlled phones in 39 flood-forecasting
agencies.  
</P>
</TEXT>
