<HEADLINE> Kenya Grants Radio, TV License to Private Media </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 29 (Xinhua) -- The Kenyan government has
granted a private company, Royal Media Services, a license to
operate radio and television stations in the country, the "Daily
Nation" reported today.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted Information and Broadcasting Minister
Johnstone Makau as saying here on Monday that the license
issued last week allowed the company to operate broadcasting
services in capital Nairobi and the cities of Nyeri and Mombasa.
</P>
<P>
The Royal Media Services, owned by a business tycoon S.K.
Macharia, is said to dwell on commercials and advertising.
</P>
<P>
The minister said that his ministry is in the process of
upgrading the Central Media Services Department into the Media
Services and Research Department.
</P>
<P>
The department will undertake research on current media
establishments with a view to keeping an updated record of their
operations, he added.
</P>
<P>
In Kenya, there are more than 60 applications for radio
operation licenses with the latest one by the BBC which seeks to
establish a FM station in Nairobi.
</P>
<P>
The private TV station registered since 1990 are Kenya
Television Network (KTN), Stellavision -- KBC 2, a merger with
M-Net of South Africa, and Cable TV. 
</P>
