<HEADLINE> Violence Mars Indonesian Democratic Party's Campaign </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, April 29 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian Democratic Party's
(PDI's) first day of election campaign in Surabaya, the second
largest city in Indonesia, ended in disarray Monday as about 5,000
loyalists of ousted PDI chief Magawati Soeharnoputri stormed the
arena, reports reaching here today said.
</P>
<P>
Several people sustained injuries from punches and flying rocks
during the scuffle which occurred at 2:00 p.m. in the city.
However, no arrests were made in the brawl which security
authorities quickly brought under control, police said.
</P>
<P>
PDI's current chairman Seorjadi unseated Megawati in a
government-backed rebel congress last year. The government has
barred Megawati from running in the election.
</P>
<P>
Many pro-Seorjadi activists crossed over and joined the
Megawati camp Monday, shouting "long live Megawati," the reports
said.
</P>
<P>
Activists of the two camps rejoiced until about 300 security
officers equipped with riot gear and armored vehicles arrived to
disperse the party.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, campaigns by the United Development Party (PPP) and
the ruling Golkar proceeded without incident.
</P>
<P>
The three political parties in Indonesia began their election
campaigns in different areas throughout the country on April 27
for the May 29 general election.
</P>
<P>
The three contestants are eyeing the 425 available seats of the
House of Representatives (DPR). Under Indonesia's political
system, the DPR has 500 seats in which 75 are provided for the
armed forces whose members do not vote.  
</P>
</TEXT>
