<DOCNO> XIE19970429.0224 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Myanmar Ready to Join AFTA: Philippine Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 29 (Xinhua) -- Philippine Undersecretary for
Foreign Affairs Rodolfo Severino said that he supported the ASEAN
Secretariat's recommendation that Myanmar is ready to integrate
into the ASEAN economy.
</P>
<P>
He said he believed the opening of the Myanmar economy to ASEAN
trade, investment and tourism would lead to political improvements
in that country, the local press today quoted him as saying on
Monday in Phuket, South Thailand, where foreign ministers of
Thailand and the Philippines are meeting today for joint
commission talks.
</P>
<P>
He said Myanmar, as a member of the World Trade Organization,
has had its trade laws in place and is ready to accede to ASEAN
Free Trade Area (AFTA) agreements.
</P>
<P>
Participation in AFTA schemes is the key criterion for ASEAN
membership.
</P>
<P>
On the question of expanding ASEAN's membership, Philippine
Foreign Secretary Domingo Siazon said his country was "very
flexible" and that his country would have to evaluate reports from
senior officials before putting forward its stand at the scheduled
informal Kuala Lumpur gathering of ASEAN foreign ministers on May
31.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN leaders decided at an informal Jakarta summit last
December to admit Cambodia, Laos and Myanmar into ASEAN
simultaneously.
</P>
<P>
Severino added that ASEAN is now concerned more about Cambodia
and not Myanmar, as Cambodia's domestic affairs could affect its
commitment to meet ASEAN requirements.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that Phnom Penh is yet to pass legislation
related to ASEAN Free Trade Area (AFTA) schemes and that its
national assembly could not convene following the grenade attack
on March 30, which killed 16 people, and the row between the
Cambodian co-prime ministers.
</P>
<P>
If any of the three countries' entry into ASEAN is to be
delayed, the other two will have to wait, according to the
principle ASEAN has agreed upon.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN has tentatively planned to admit the three countries this
year, to mark the regional group's the 30th anniversary and to
realize ASEAN founders' aspiration to include all 10 countries in
the region.
</P>
<P>
The Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) now has
seven members -- Brunei, Indonesia, Malaysia, the Philippines,
Singapore, Thailand and Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
Late last week, the US government banned new investment by
Americans in Myanmar and requested ASEAN not to accept Myanmar
into the grouping.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
