<HEADLINE> Small Parties in Nepal Plan to Form United Front </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, April 29 (Xinhua) -- Small political parties in
Nepal are planning to form a united front to counter what they
alleged a conspiracy against them by two major parties.
</P>
<P>
The proposed Left Democratic Front is to include the 18 small
parties which have been launching a series of protests against an
earlier decision by the Election Commission (EC) not to allow them
to use their own symbols in the forthcoming local elections, said
sources here today.
</P>
<P>
Leaders of the parties, most of them holding no seats in
parliament, at a meeting here Monday alleged that the commission's
decision was a conspiracy of the two largest parties to undermine
smaller parties.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was organized to study the possibility of the small
parties coming together as a front to run against major parties in
next month's local elections, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
Nepal's two largest parties, ruling partner the Communist Party
of Nepal (United Marxist Leninist, CPN-UML) and main opposition
the Nepali Congress (NC), currently control most parliamentary
seats and local authorities in the country.
</P>
<P>
The small parties have also called a nation-wide general strike
Wednesday in protest against the Election Commission's decision.
</P>
</TEXT>
