<HEADLINE> Rebels Kill 2 Workers in Indonesia's Irian Jaya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, April 29 (Xinhua) -- A separatist rebel group, the
Free Papua Movement (OPM), in Indonesia's Irian Jaya province,
killed two road surveyors, the official Antara news agency
reported today.
</P>
<P>
A group of armed men believed to be OPM members attacked a camp
of a road construction company in Akiba village on Sunday and shot
dead two road surveyors there, said the agency.
</P>
<P>
Eight other workers escaped to the nearby forest and their
whereabouts remained unknown, it added.
</P>
<P>
A military team was sent to the site of the incident on Monday,
head of the district's military command Lt. Col. Harry Risdianto
was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
In January 1996, the group took 26 people hostage, including
seven Europeans. All were released or escaped in May last year
during a rescue operation in which two Indonesian hostages were
killed.
</P>
<P>
The group also kidnapped 16 workers of a logging company in
central Irian Jaya last August. Two hostages were killed and the
rest were released or escaped later.
</P>
<P>
The OPM, known as a security disturbance group, has been
fighting for a separate state in the area since the early 1960s.
</P>
</TEXT>
