<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nepali Government Justifies Decision on Rhino Gifts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, April 29 (Xinhua) -- The Nepali government said
today that its decision to send two rhinos as gifts to Britain did
not violate the international convention against trade in
endangered wildlife species.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Forest in a press release said that the
transfer of two female baby rhinos to the London Zoo was approved
by wildlife protecting authorities in Nepal and the United Kingdom
as part of an international conservation program for the species.
</P>
<P>
The Secretariat of the Convention on International Trade in
Endangered Species of Wild Flora and Fauna (CITES) in Switzerland
also authorized the transfer, it added.
</P>
<P>
The two unicorn rhino calves were shipped out of Nepal Monday
by a flight of German airline Lufthansa for London amid strong
opposition from local environmental activists.
</P>
<P>
The Lufthansa flight was coincidentally the last passenger
flight of the German Airline from Kathmandu as it ends its
passenger operation in Nepal from May, 1997 due to financial
reasons.
</P>
<P>
According to the ministry, the government decided in 1995 to
provide the two rhinos to the London Zoo as gifts for the purpose
of scientific research after nearly three years' pursuit from the
British side.
</P>
<P>
Nepal at present has some 500 rhinos in the Chitwan National
Wildlife Park, the species' only habitat in the country, the
ministry said.
</P>
<P>
Local environmentalists had called on the government to scrap
the rhino gift plan, arguing that the CITES prohibits any form of
trade of the rhino and the country lacks a transparent policy on
such a case.
</P>
<P>
They alleged that a semi-governmental conservation agency took
400,000 US dollars from the British Zoological Society for the
deal.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970429.0229 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bulgaria-Romania Optical Telecommunications Cable Completed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SOFIA, April 28 (Xinhua) -- Bulgaria will soon link its northern
border city of Ruse with the city of Giurgiu in Romania through an
optical telecommunications cable.
</P>
<P>
The optical cable, with a capacity of 350,000 speech paths, has
been laid and will soon be put into operation. It is part of a
planned optical cable network between Sofia and Bucharest, the
capitals of the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The operation of the optical cable would not only help
guarantee high quality telecommunications between Bulgaria and
Romania, but also offer services for countries in western and
central Europe as well as the Near East.
</P>
<P>
Over the recent two years, Bulgaria has laid a total length of
211 kilometers of optical cables and built 11 program-controlled
switchboards.
</P>
<P>
An optical cable network has connected Bulgaria with
Yugoslavia, Turkey, Greece and Romania.
</P>
<P>
But experts complained that the development of Bulgaria's
telecommunication industry is still far from keeping up with the
country's economic development.
</P>
<P>
Latest statistics showed that there are 37 telephones for every
100 people in the country with a population of 8.5 million. Of the
country's 2,445 switchboards, only 11 are program controlled.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
