<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arson Evidences Found in Philippine Hotel Fire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 29 (Xinhua) -- Investigators have discovered
material evidences that could link the cause of a Philippine hotel
fire, which killed 27 people in the southern city of Cotabato, to
arson, the Philippine News Agency said today.
</P>
<P>
Investigation team sent to Cotabato by the government from
Manila to look into the Imperial Hotel fire on April 26 recently
found two gasoline containers in rooms 305 and 319 of the burned
establishment, the agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Room 305, earlier reserved as prayer room for Autonomous Region
in Muslim Mindanao Governor Nur Misuari's guests who were at the
hotel to witness his state-of-the-region address originally
scheduled for April 28, was the place pointed to as where the fire
started.
</P>
<P>
Misuari later postponed his state address.
</P>
<P>
Virgilio Tobias, regional director of the country's Bureau of
Fire Protection, was quoted by the agency as saying that the
gasoline containers were already brought to Manila for laboratory
tests.
</P>
<P>
No official result has been declared yet by Tobias on their
investigation but he could not rule out the possibility of arson
following the discovery of the containers.
</P>
<P>
He said that a special task force to investigate the tragedy
was expected to come up with an official report on the case by May
2.
</P>
<P>
The task force is composed of the provincial fire marshal of
North Cotabato, the city fire marshal inspector and members from
the Bureau of Fire Protection in Manila.  
</P>
</TEXT>
