<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dhaka to Raise Prices of Fertilizer, Fuel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, April 29 (Xinhua) -- The Bangladeshi government is
expected to announce an upward adjustment of the sensitive
fertilizer prices before the forthcoming budget for 1997-98 year
beginning from the first day of July, according to official
sources.
</P>
<P>
A similar decision to raise gasoline prices might follow. In
fact the new budget would require upward price adjustments for
some more utility items such as water, gas and electricity, said
the sources.
</P>
<P>
But finance ministry officials said the authorities would not
do anything in a haste.
</P>
<P>
Dhaka has been under pressure for a long time to make
adjustments in the prices of these items for budget balance and
also to comply with international donors' requests.
</P>
<P>
The donors' community is pressing the government to increase
the urea price, which is heavily subsidized and quiet lower than
the market price of neighboring India.
</P>
<P>
To provide cheap fertilizer to farmers, the Bangladeshi
government is now selling urea at 3725 Taka (about 93 U.S.
dollars) per ton as against the cost of production at 5011 Taka
(about 125 dollars) per ton.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that the government's fertilizer subsidy this
year would be as high as 4.83 billion Taka (about 120 million U.S.
dollars).
</P>
<P>
"Increasing fertilizer prices is a sensitive issue. The
government's priority lies in reaching urea to farmers at a
cheaper price," said a high-ranking official from the Finance
Ministry.
</P>
<P>
"But experience showed that it was not the farmers but the
marketing agents and smugglers who were taking the bigger chunk of
this advantage. Therefore, a reasonable increase in prices will
not significantly affect the farmers," he said.
</P>
<P>
Although the acreage under cultivation and food production over
these years remained almost steady, the demand for urea doubled
from 1.22 million tons in 1992 to 2.3 million tons in 1997.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
