<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greece Backs Albania's Interim Government </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIRANA, April 28 (Xinhua) -- The Greek government would give
its full support to Albanian Prime Minister Bashkim Fino and his
all-party interim government, visiting Greek Defense Minister Akis
Tsohatzopoulos said today.
</P>
<P>
When meeting with Fino, who was appointed as prime minister in
mid-March, Tsohatzopoulos said that Albania and Greece should help
each other not only because the two countries are neighbors and
enjoy traditional friendship but also because they share the
responsibility for safeguarding the stability of the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
Fino agreed and also spoke highly of the development of the
good-neighborly relationship between the two countries, said a
statement issued by the prime minister's office later today.
</P>
<P>
Fino said preparing for the scheduled June parliamentary
elections was the priority of his government, which, transitional
in nature, would come to the end of its mandate by that time.
</P>
<P>
He added that the presence of a 6,000-member multinational
protection force in Albania would guarantee the elections to be
held in a peaceful atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
The collapse of shaky investment schemes, into which thousands
of Albanians put their life savings, sparked widespread unrest in
the Balkan country in January and protests mushroomed across the
country. They quickly erupted into armed conflict across the
country in March.
</P>
<P>
Protesters demanded repayment of their money and the opposition
Socialist Party called for the resignation of President Sali
Berisha.
</P>
<P>
Fino, an economist from the Socialist Party, was invited by the
president to form a new government on March 12. This government
adopted effective measures to placate the unrest, and order is
being restored in the country.
</P>
<P>
On March 25, the United Nations Security Council passed a
resolution authorizing the dispatch of a 6,000-member, Italian-led
multinational force for three months to protect relief operations
in Albania. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
