<HEADLINE> No Civil War in Albania, Says European Delegation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIRANA, April 28 (Xinhua) -- European Parliament Vice President
Guido Podeska said here today that there is no civil war in
Albania.
</P>
<P>
Podeska, who was visiting albania at the head of an European
Parliamentary delegation designed to find out the real situation
in Albania, has met with leaders of the Albanian government and
various political parties and visited chaotic cities of Vlora
and Shkoder.
</P>
<P>
More than 200 people have reportedly been killed in Albania,
which has been engulfed by chaos sparked last December by the
collapse of pyramid investment schemes in which thousands of
Albanians lost their money.
</P>
<P>
Much of southern Albania is now still under the control of
armed protesters who insisted President Sali Berisha resign over
the fraudulent investment schemes.
</P>
<P>
An Italian-led multinational force approved by the United
Nations is carrying out humanitarian relief operations in the
nation.
</P>
<P>
Podeska said at a press conference before leaving the Balkan
nation that the situation in southern Albanian city of Vlora is
comparatively quiet while the northern city of Shkoder appeared
seriously chaotic due to ruffians' activities.
</P>
<P>
Albanian Prime Minister Bashkim Fino told the European
delegation that nothing of the sort as described by some foreign
press media has occurred in Albania. There is no civil war, ethnic
war or south-north war in the country, he said.
</P>
<P>
Fino said that "the citizens' committees" established in
southern Albania were actually committees set up by honest
intellectuals under conditions in which police authorities were
paralyzed and many police left their jobs.
</P>
<P>
The committees, which cannot be lumped together with armed
criminals, will die out of themselves when local authorities are
restored, he said.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister promised that his government will crack down
on armed bandits. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
