<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Latin American Leaders Criticize U.S. Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 28 (Xinhua) -- Some Latin American leaders
today slammed the United States for introducing unilateral trade
and drug policy towards Latin American countries.
</P>
<P>
The leaders made the remarks at a two-day meeting held at the
Carter Center in Altanta. The meeting, sponsored by former
U.S. President Jimmy Carter, was aimed at mapping out a
"hemispheric agenda" for the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
Accusing the U.S. of foot-dragging in world trade, the leaders
complained that little progress has been made since December 1994
when leaders from 34 countries in the west hemisphere met in Miami
and pledged to create a free trade zone by 2005.
</P>
<P>
Bolivian President Gonzlo Sanchez said that the expansion of
free trade between the U.S. and other countries were opposed by
some Republicans in the U.S. Congress.
</P>
<P>
The U.S.'s controversial "certification" on other countries'
anti-drug efforts was also criticized at the meeting.
</P>
<P>
In its annual report, the U.S. State Department "certifies" and
"decertifies" 32 countries on their anti-drug efforts. The U.S.
will impose sanctions on, or cut off aid to, the "decertified"
nations.
</P>
<P>
"Certification...does not make for partnership, it does not
make for friendship... it is obvious that the process does more
harm than good, " said Jamaican Prime Minister P.J. Patterson.
</P>
<P>
Cesar Gaviria, the secretary general of the Organization of
American States (OAS), said that the certification is unilateral
and should be avoided in future.
</P>
<P>
In Washington, U.S. Assistant Secretary of State for
Inter-American Affairs Jeffrey Davidow told a forum that the
annual U.S. assessment of other countries in fighting drugs has
become an "unnecessarily traumatic ritual."
</P>
<P>
"I agree it has become...unnecessarily traumatic yearly
ritual," he admitted.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
