<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Bangladesh's Stock Market Hit by Scandal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, April 29 (Xinhua) -- The Dhaka Stock Exchange (DSE), the
main bourse of Bangladesh, witnessed a continuous bearish trend in
recent weeks after the investor's confidence was heavily hit by
this country's biggest-ever stock scandal.
</P>
<P>
Last Sunday, the benchmark DSE All Share Price Index nose-dived
by 5.42 percent to 969.70 points, a few points down from the level
which the present government inherited 10 months ago. The index
further slid down to 899.38 on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Ever since the Awami (people's) League led by Sheikh Hasina
assumed power last June, the key index rode a bull run amidst
alleged manipulation until it reached a dizzying height of 3648.74
on November 5 of last year.
</P>
<P>
The bubble burst finally and investors, mostly new without any
experience, saw share prices falling everyday, making them lose
all their savings.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Securities and Exchange Commission (SEC), the
watchdog of this country's capital market, submitted a probe
report on the unusual ups and downs of the stock prices, which
dragged the benchmark index to a mercurial journey down.
</P>
<P>
In that report, eight well-known listed companies and seven
broker firms were charged with manipulating share prices through
fraudulent means during the bull run last year.
</P>
<P>
On April 2, the government filed the cases and the court issued
arrest warrants against the major business leaders and stock
brokers involved in the market manipulation. However, all those
accused were later granted anticipatory bail.
</P>
<P>
"No doubt the market would be panicky since the scandal
indicated that the DSE has a long way to go to turn into a
well-regulated and mature stock market," said a market observer.
</P>
<P>
Besides, the recent panic also intensified following a report
statement by central bank Governor Lutfar Rahman Sarker that the
country's banking system was on the verge of collapse, said a
senior broker of the DSE.
</P>
<P>
Sarker estimated the amount of outstanding bank loans at 130
billion Taka (about 3 billion U.S. dollars) and said the nation's
banks would not be able to survive with the huge debt burden.
</P>
<P>
The warning also rattled the stock market as most investors and
brokers heavily depended on bank loans, the broker added.
</P>
<P>
"There is no sign of stabilizing the market... the prime
minister should intervene now, she should remove all who failed to
manage the market," said an investor, who lost a considerable
amount of money in the market.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a large number of agitated kerb traders staged a
protest rally before the DSE building, protesting the continued
price erosion and demanding the resignation of Finance Minister
Shah AMS Kibria.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, the authorities said they were up with
measures to rescue the bourse from the slump though a number of
financial and regulatory measures taken earlier went in vain.
</P>
<P>
"We are now considering a number of options to stabilize the
market. Some of them are the continuation of the earlier
measures," said the SEC chairman Harunoor Rashid.
</P>
<P>
He said the new measures are likely to be announced shortly.
"But, at the moment, I can't disclose those," he maintained.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
