<DOCNO> XIE19970429.0244 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka's Tourist Industry Recovers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, April 29 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka's tourist industry has
recovered this year following a lean year last year when a drop of
25 percent in arrivals was recorded.
</P>
<P>
Earnings from tourism plunged to 175 million US dollars in 1996
from 225 million US dollars the previous year following several
bomb attacks in Colombo by Tamil rebels.
</P>
<P>
However, tourist arrivals in the first quarter of this year
rose by 17 percent over the same period in 1996 to 101,760.
Arrivals in March alone rose by 29 percent to 34,098 from 26,442
in the same month last year.
</P>
<P>
The recovery is attributed to the improved security situation
in the country and the promotional work by both the government and
the private sector.
</P>
<P>
Tourist Board sources expects tourist arrivals to be about
400,000 this year, which was the figure for 1995.
</P>
<P>
Average hotel occupancy during the current season was around 50
percent with some hotels being almost full, according to the
sources.
</P>
<P>
Sri Lankan hotel stocks have risen already by 12.1 percent this
month as a result of political stability, lower corporate
borrowing rates and expectations of better first quarter results,
the sources added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
