<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Disputed Win Helps America to Top Spot at Group B </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HELSINKI, April 28 (Xinhua) -- Ted Donato's disputed goal with
46 seconds left in the first period helped the United States beat
Norway 3-1 in the ice hockey world championship Monday.
</P>
<P>
The win moved the Americans level with Sweden atop the Group B
standings played in Turku with two wins apiece from their opening
two games.
</P>
<P>
Russia, Slovakia and Italy also won their Monday's matches to
keep alive their hopes of advancing to the medal round.
</P>
<P>
Norway led the Americans 1-0 by Svien Enok Norstebo.
</P>
<P>
After Vancouver Canuck enforcer Don Brashear pulled the U.S.
even it looked as if the teams would head into the first break
tied until Donato stepped into the Norwegian goalmouth behind
netminder Robert Schistad and stabbed home a loose puck.
</P>
<P>
Norway protested the goal but after checking with the video
replay judges, referee Leonid Vaisfled allowed it to stand.
</P>
<P>
In another Group B action, Bruno Zarrillo scored twice as Italy
came from a three goal deficit to beat Latvia 5-4 for its first
win of the championship.
</P>
<P>
Latvia lost its opening match to the United States by the same
score on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
In Helsinki, Russia struggled for much of its clash with
Germany before a late three-goal burst secured a 5-1 win.
</P>
<P>
Slovakia who fought to a 2-2 draw against Russia on Sunday kept
its hopes alive with a 5-3 win over France after recovering from
two goals down.
</P>
<P>
The results left Russia and Slovakia with three points, one
behind defending champion the Czech Republic who head Group A with
four.  
</P>
</TEXT>
