<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mexican Cinematographer Gabriel Figueroa Dies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, April 28 (Xinhua) -- Mexican cinematographer
Gabriel Figueroa, one of the pioneers of the so-called "golden
age" of national cinema, died Sunday at the age of 90 and will be
buried today in Mexico's capital city.
</P>
<P>
Figueroa died of cardiorespiratory arrest Sunday evening.
</P>
<P>
The Mexican cinematographer circle considered him a fundamental
part of national cinema and a genuine hero and artist of the
camera lens since he created a whole new school in the art of
moving pictures.
</P>
<P>
Mexican President Ernesto Zelillo said in a brief message that
Mexico has lost the photographer that give Mexican cinema its
greatest projection and, without a doubt, one of its most
important creative artists in the cinematography world.
</P>
<P>
There will always be admiration and gratitude to Figueroa for
his artistic legacy that has inspired many generations of Mexicans
to appreciate Mexico's history and culture, he added.
</P>
<P>
"Don Gaby," as Gabriel Figueroa was fondly addressed, was born
in Mexico City on April 24, 1907. He witnessed the flowering
of national cinematography in its golden age.
</P>
<P>
According to local experts, his talent in the art of motion
pictures was his ability to amalgamate rural and urban life, give
movies a very national touch and, at the same time, gain
international recognition. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
