<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Central China City to Ban Smoking </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, April 29 (Xinhua) -- A smoking ban is set to take
effect in Changsha, the capital of central China's Hunan province,
on May 1.
</P>
<P>
a government regulation prohibits smoking on passenger trains,
ships, planes, in buses and taxis, and in waiting rooms and ticket
offices at railway stations, airports, and ports.
</P>
<P>
Hospitals, schools, cinemas, department stores, banks, dance
halls, and video arcades have also been designated smoking-free
areas.
</P>
<P>
Soon, "No smoking" signs will be visible in gymnasiums,
libraries, banks, post and telecom offices, exhibition halls, art
galleries, and museums according to the regulation.
</P>
<P>
Six provinces and municipalities, along with 40 small and
medium-sized cities in China have so far adopted regulations that
forbid smoking in public places.  
</P>
</TEXT>
