<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Drive to Combat Killer Viral Hepatitis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 29 (Xinhua) -- China is to launch a massive
training program in a bid to combat viral hepatitis, one of
China's most serious public health problems.
</P>
<P>
The activities will include lectures for patients to increase
knowledge on hepatitis prevention and treatment, according to
today's "China Daily".
</P>
<P>
Training programs will also be organized for doctors to improve
their skills in diagnosing and treating viral hepatitis cases, the
paper said.
</P>
<P>
The Academic Promotion in Viral Hepatitis and Liver Diseases
(ChinaHep), an independent professional association that is
composed of 44 leading hepatitis physicians from across the
country, has developed educational programs in the light of
Chinese conditions.
</P>
<P>
ChinaHep statistics showed that each year, between 500,000 and
one million people throughout the country are newly diagnosed with
chronic hepatitis, with 20 to 30 percent developing fatal
illnesses like cancer of the liver.
</P>
<P>
And there is no common understanding of the diagnosis and
treatment of hepatitis.
</P>
<P>
Some doctors can not make an accurate diagnose of the type of
viral hepatitis, and can not prescribe effective medicines.
</P>
<P>
Many patients know little about the disease and may be easily
cheated by exaggerated advertisements for medicines and therapies
which are often expensive and of little or no effect, the
newspaper said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
