<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pak-China Economic Cooperation to Be Strengthened: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, April 29 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan's President Farooq
Leghari believes that economic cooperation between Pakistan and
China is to be further strengthened.
</P>
<P>
"There is a scope for increasing the volume of trade between
our two countries," Leghari told the Chinese media here last night
before his departure on a two-day working visit to China.
</P>
<P>
Leghari said that during his stay in Beijing he will hold talks
with Chinese President Jiang Zemin on bilateral relations,
regional and international issues, particularly on matters of
deepening economic cooperation between Pakistan and China.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan and China enjoy "very deep and brotherly relations,"
the president said, adding that "we are neighbors, and the best
friends in the world, the relations between our two countries are
ideal."
</P>
<P>
Pakistan and China, as the two brotherly countries, share "a
commonality on almost all international issues," Leghari said. The
two countries "support each other very strongly at all
international fora," he added.
</P>
<P>
There is "very good government-to-government relationship"
between Pakistan and China, and the two countries also enjoy "very
good cooperation in the defense field," said Leghari.
</P>
<P>
"We want to do now is to increase the level and volume of our
trade and economic cooperation," the president stressed.
</P>
<P>
Leghari said the frequent high-level contacts between Pakistan
and China will certainly promote the development of the bilateral
relations.
</P>
<P>
The president said that China is a country which has made rapid
economic progress. Pakistan, too, also has the great potential to
grow in economic terms.
</P>
<P>
There are broad prospects for the two countries to further
strengthen their economic and trade cooperation, Leghari said.
</P>
<P>
Leghari is visiting China for the second time as the president.
He first visited China in November 1994.
</P>
<P>
The president was seen off here last night by Zhang Chunxiang,
Charge d' Affaires of the Chinese Embassy to Pakistan as well as
other Chinese diplomats.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Minister Gohar Ayub Khan, Commerce Minister Ishaq Dar
and Deputy governor of the State Bank of Pakistan Mahfooz Alam are
the main members of the president's entourage this time.  
</P>
</TEXT>
