<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai's Labour Marts Help Laid-off Get New Jobs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 29 (Xinhua) -- Shanghai will set up more
re-employment centers this year to find laid-off workers new jobs
and create a labour market, today's "China Daily" reports.
</P>
<P>
The Beijing based newspaper quotes Ye Mingzhong, deputy
director of the Shanghai Municipal Labour Bureau as saying that
Shanghai will establish centers in more sectors: light industry,
machinery and electronics, chemical, metallurgy and building
materials, and instrument-manufacturing.
</P>
<P>
Ye estimated that 250,000 laid-off workers will use the centres
this year. The centers help laid-off workers enroll in job
training programmes and seek new jobs for them.
</P>
<P>
About 600,000 to 750,000 people will have to be allocated new
jobs during the 1996-2000 period. The increasing number of
laid-off workers is caused by the industrial restructuring and
economic development across China.
</P>
<P>
Last year, 230,000 workers came to the re-employment centers
for help, including 115,000 from the textile industry. The textile
sector encountered unprecedented difficulties as Shanghai moves
into a market economy.
</P>
<P>
The re-employment service center for the textile industry has
set up various training programmes for laid-off workers. Last
year, the center helped 58,000 unemployed workers find new
jobs, The paper says.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
