<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Anti-Smuggling Exhibition Draws Public Attention in Shanghai </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, April 29 (Xinhua) -- An exhibition on the crack down
on smuggling by China's Customs officials has been well received
by citizens in Shanghai, the leading manufacturing center in
China.
</P>
<P>
As China's largest port, Shanghai is coveted by many
smugglers. Leaders of Shanghai have stressed on many occasions
that "Shanghai will never become a smuggling conduit",
and have taken measures to combat against smuggling activities.
</P>
<P>
Huang Ju, secretary of the Shanghai Municipal Committee of the
Chinese Communist Party, and 300 other leaders attended the
opening ceremony of the exhibition and vowed that they will fight
against such illegal activities.
</P>
<P>
The third anti-smuggling exhibition sponsored by China's
General Administration of Customs has drawn close attention from
Chinese top leaders such as President Jiang Zemin, who has given
important instructions to publicize anti-smuggling operations.
</P>
<P>
With the development of China's economy and opening wider to
the outside world, the struggle against smuggling has become more
difficult. In the past ten years, China's customs officials have
solved 94,000 smuggling cases, and confiscated 20,000 smuggled
cars and 30,000 kilograms of drugs..
</P>
<P>
The exhibition has selected 400 objects in order to show the
seriousness and complexity of the anti-smuggling effort. Some of
Shanghai Customs' achievements have also been exhibited. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
