<DOCNO> XIE19970429.0269 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Background: ABCs of Basic Law of Hong Kong SAR (51-52) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 29 (Xinhua) -- Following are the ABCs of the
Basic Law of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (51-52) in
a question-and-answer format:
</P>
<P>
Question: What are qualifications for public servants in the
government of the Hong Kong SAR?
</P>
<P>
Answer: It is important to keep the existing civil service to
maintain the stability and prosperity of Hong Kong. The existing
civil service basically suits Hong Kong's economic
development. Keeping this system basically unchanged will
contribute to the Hong Kong SAR's stability and prosperity.
</P>
<P>
According to the Basic Law, public servants in all government
departments of the Hong Kong SAR must be permanent residents of
the region; foreign nationals among the SAR's permanent residents
may also serve as public servants in government departments
(except for certain high positions); and all public servants
serving in the Hong Kong government before the establishment of
the Hong Kong SAR may remain employed and retain their seniority
with pay, allowances, benefits and conditions of service no less
favourable than before.
</P>
<P>
Non-permanent residents of the Hong Kong SAR, such as people in
the mainland, are not eligible to serve as public servants in Hong
Kong.
</P>
<P>
Question: Will people's deputies to the National People's
Congress form Hong Kong automatically become public servants of
the Hong Kong SAR?
</P>
<P>
Answer: The answer is no. This is because NPC deputies and
public servants are different in nature.
</P>
<P>
Deputies are representatives of Hong Kong people in different
walks of life, and being a deputy is not a profession, whereas
being a public servant is. An NPC deputy can become a public
servant only when he or she is employed by the government in the
capacity of an ordinary Hong Kong citizen. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970429.0270 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Echoes From The Mercosur (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
RIO DE JANEIRO -- Brazilian trade with the Mercosur increased
at an average of nearly 19 percent during the first quarter of
this year compared with the same period in 1996 with 4.57 billion
dollars worth of trade.
</P>
<P>
Brazilian exports to the Mercosur reached 2.2 billion dollars
and its imports 2.37 billion dollars with a 170 billion-dollar
trade deficit for the corresponding period.
</P>
<P>
Brazilian sales to its Mercosur partners increased 20.6
percent during the first quarter compared with the same period
in 1996 while its imports rose 17.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
The Mercosur is Brazil's second biggest market surpassed only
by the European Union.
</P>
<P>
MONTEVIDEO -- The Uruguayan and Argentine armies will carry
out joint military maneuvres between June 9-13 in the western
border department of Rio Negro, Uruguay.
</P>
<P>
Dubbed "Operation Ceibo", the exercises will be the first of
its kind in which effectives from both countries will work
together on a large scale.
</P>
<P>
Military sources said that about 1,000 effectives will
take part in the exercise.
</P>
<P>
MONTEVIDEO -- The administrative commission of the
Bolivia-Mercosur Agreement was installed in the head offices of
the Latin American Integration Association head offices in this
capital on April 23 to provide continuity to the implementation
of the agreement signed last December.
</P>
<P>
The commission will have the responsibility to watch over the
compliance of the agreement and its protocols and to determine the
forms of negotiations and the deadlines for reaching its
objectives.
</P>
<P>
ASUNCION -- The joint parliamentary committee of the
Mercosur, which had an emergency meeting in this city on April
21, recommended that the Brazilian government lift the tariff
barriers it imposed on its bloc partners.
</P>
<P>
In a document addressed to the Brazilian government, the
legislators taking part in the meeting expressed their concern
over the implementation of the provisional measure of March 25.
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, the parliamentary committee pointed out that the
Mercosur should create a mechanism through which any measure of an
economic nature -that may affect the interests of other members of
the bloc- must be consulted with the other members before it can
be implemented by any state.
</P>
<P>
ASUNCION -- On April 24, Cattle ranchers of the four Mercosur
countries officialized the creation of a Mercosur Rural Federation
in this capital city to fight trade protectionism.
</P>
<P>
Jose Ignacio Bobadilla, the president of Paraguay's Rural
Association was elected pro tempore president of the federation
since Paraguay is currently exercising the same function in this
regional. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970429.0271 </DOCNO>
