<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Race Won't Be for title of Fastest Man, Says Bailey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 28 (Xinhua) -- Donovan Bailey says his
150-meter race against Michael Johnson on June 1 in Toronto will
not be a battle for the title of "world's fastest man".
</P>
<P>
The world recored holder and Olympic champion in the 100 meters
was quoted as saying in Austin, Ttexas, the race will be about
Canada vs. the United States, flamboyance against intensity and a
short sprinter taking on a long sprinter.
</P>
<P>
Johnson is the world record holder in the 200 meters and
Olympic champion in the 200 and 400 meters.
</P>
<P>
"The fastest man runs on a straightaway," Bailey was quoted by
a report reaching here as saying, alluding to the fact the
150-meter race against Johnson will include 75 meters of curve and
75 meters of straightaway.
</P>
<P>
"Michael and I are the two biggest stars in track and field
worldwide," Bailey said.
</P>
<P>
Bailey also said the race is more about marketing a sport that
he says is suffering an identity crisis. Each will get 500,000
U.S. dollars for showing up in Toronto, and the winner will take
home 1 million U.S. dollars.  
</P>
</TEXT>
