<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Deports Ex-Auschwitz Camp Guard </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 28 (Xinhua) -- The United States ordered an
ex-guard of the Nazi Auschwitz concentration camp in Michigan
deported, the Justice Department announced today.
</P>
<P>
Chief U.S. Immigration Judge Michael Creppy found that
Ferninand Hammer participated in persecuting people at the
Auschwitz concentration camp in Poland and other places during
1944 and 1945.
</P>
<P>
Hammer was also found to once guard prisoners transported
between Auschwitz and Sachsenhausen camp near Berlin in 1945.
</P>
<P>
Hammer, 75, was stripped of his U.S. citizenship on grounds
that he lied about his role in the war. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970429.0277 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Hopes for Peaceful Transition in Zaire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 28 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
has sent an envoy to Zaire to try to press parties in the war-torn
country to hold elections, a State Department spokesman announced
today.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press briefing, State Department spokesman
Nicholas Burns said that U.S. Ambassador to the U.N. Bill
Richardson, who arrived in the Zairian capital of Kinsasa earlier
today, was carrying a letter from Clinton to Zairian President
Mobutu Seko.
</P>
<P>
"I can say the letter speaks to the hope that the United States
has for a peaceful process towards democracy in Zaire," said
Burns, who declined to give the contents of the letter.
</P>
<P>
Richardson will press Mobutu and rebel leader Laurent Kabila to
agree on a cease-fire and to encourage them to work together on a
peaceful political transition, according to Burns.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. envoy will also investigate the 100,000 Rwandan
refugees in Zaire whose plight has become a matter of increasing
concern, Burns added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970429.0278 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kinkel: EU Should Have More Capability to Act in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, April 28 (Xinhua) -- German Foreign Minister Klaus Kinkel
today said that the European Union (EU) should have more
"capability to act" in foreign and security affairs.
</P>
<P>
During a meeting in Hamburg with Hans van Mierlo, Dutch foreign
minister who now holds the rotating presidency of the Council of
the EU, Kinkel said the EU need to make common foreign and
security policies visible to the outside world. Otherwise, the
credibility of the EU would be threatened, he added.
</P>
<P>
Stressing the necessity to reform the current EU practice of
consensus decision-making, Kinkel said, "We need a transition to
majority voting." Consensus need to be retained only in the area
of defense, he added.
</P>
<P>
During the talks, Kinkel also reiterated his call for a
step-by-step integration of the Western European Union into the EU
structure. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970429.0279 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Dollar Strengthens Further </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, April 28 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. dollar ended mostly
higher today as traders held the belief that the Group of Seven's
weekend summit communique indicated its reluctance to halt the
currency's ascent.
</P>
<P>
Financial officials from Britain, Canada, France, Germany,
Italy, Japan and the United States met in Washington Sunday,
sending a signal that they would not act aggressively to stop the
dollar, which has risen more than 12 percent against the mark and
nearly 10 percent against the yen this year.
</P>
<P>
The dollar briefly hit a 38-month high of 1.7386 marks in early
Asian dealings before settling in New York at 1.7330 marks, up
from 1.7270 Friday. The dollar ended at 126.98 yen, up from
126.25. The pound cost 1.6247 U.S. dollars, up from 1.6231 U.S.
dollars.
</P>
<P>
Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with Friday:
5.8385 French francs, up from 5.8270; 1.4740 Swiss francs, up from
1.4695; 1,718.00 Italian lire, up from 1,717.00; 1.3998 Canadian
dollars, up from 1.3967. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970429.0280 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Calls for Redressal of Anomalous UN Council </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, April 28 (Xinhua) -- China stressed today that
the key to the enlargement of the Security Council rested with the
redressal of its long-standing anomalous composition in terms of
geographical representation and representation between developed
and developing countries.
</P>
<P>
Reiterating the basic position on the reform at a meeting of
the Working Group on the reform of the Security Council, Chinese
Ambassador Wang Xuexian said that China supported reasonable and
appropriate expansion of the Security Council.
</P>
<P>
"The key to the enlargement of the Security Council lies in
redressing the long-standing anomaly in geographical
representation and in representation between developed and
developing countries in the composition of the Security Council.
No reform plan should aggravate such anomaly," he said.
</P>
<P>
Though the working group had intensive discussions on the
reform for more than three years, there still existed serious and
profound differences among countries on many major questions, he
noted.
</P>
<P>
As the question affected the interest of all countries, full
and patient discussions were necessary so as to reach consensus or
at least be close to consensus, he said.
</P>
<P>
"This is the only way to ensure that a reformed Security
Council represents to the greatest extent the will of the general
membership and better fulfills the important responsibilities
entrusted to it by the Charter," he said.
</P>
<P>
As the final reform plan of the Security Council needed to be
carefully cultivated by the entire membership, "we are not in
favor of setting a time frame for reform or forcing a vote on it,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
"Haste makes waste. It may not only adversely affect the work
of the Security Council and the United Nations, but also sharpen
the contradictions among member states and cast a shadow on
regional or even world peace and security," he said.
</P>
<P>
The UN Charter, as the political and legal basis of the United
Nations, had stood the test of history. It was the guarantee for
the smooth development of the United Nations. Amendment of the
Charter was a major and sensitive political issue on which
opinions should be widely solicited and prudent discussions
conducted, he stressed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
